Final thoughts \n This guide has attempted to provide insight into various aspects of the current status of laboratory testing of cannabis in the U.S. By extension, it has required a closer look at many non-testing or tangentially related aspects of cannabis, including history, regulations, standards, methods, equipment, and software. The guide has also attempted to look at the potential future of testing, a more difficult feat that has required inspection of\u2014and speculation on\u2014a mix of statistics and politics, as well as government and social policy and how they may all affect the future of cannabis testing. We learned that many point fingers at the U.S. federal government for being responsible for several cannabis-related issues, including lack of clear government support for cannabis research, lack of standardization of testing and analysis methods for said research, and wavering policy that remains inconsistent at best. At root is the fact that the federal government maintains cannabis (and its constituents) as a Schedule I drug, by extension declaring that it has no respectable medical use. This and related decisions have slowed down the academic study of cannabis (at least in the U.S.), including its analysis, quality testing, and research and use as a medical treatment. The development, implementation, and reassessment of cultivation and testing standards and methods have largely been piecemeal; additionally, those efforts have been enacted in an environment where, despite the legal status in a state, fear that the federal government will inevitably intervene slows progress even further.\nDespite these barriers, the speed at which U.S. states have adopted some form of legalization of cannabis has pushed scientists and researchers to collaborate and improve standards and methods. Necessity continues to be the mother of invention, driving those in the industry to adapt or perish in a difficult, inconsistent market. State officials are teaming up at industry conferences and sharing ideas. Non-profit organizations are joining forces with major standards agencies to expand and improve good laboratory practices. Researchers\u2014whether on their own or with the help of others internationally\u2014are learning more about the various cannabinoids and their interaction with terpenes, driving new insight into potential therapeutic remedies. Overall public perception about marijuana consumption and use is gradually shifting towards a positive light, even when so little is still understood about the long-term ramifications of its use. Commercial interests are taking notice, and so are international treaty makers. All of this adds up to forward momentum in the cannabis industry, with warts and all.\nMany factors will affect the future of cannabis regulation, testing, and research; in the process, we're certain to see both ups and downs as political and social climates continue to change. However, as marijuana consumption and hemp-based manufacturing methods continue to see expanded support, consumers and manufacturers, as well as all those involved in between, will always clamor for a safer product that is \"as advertised.\" Laboratory analysis will play an important role in that effort, whether it's in the medical research lab, the quality control lab, or the manufacturer's lab. It will be imperative for all interested parties to further work together to ensure methods are sound and standardized in a realistic and beneficial way to ensure that in the end consumers will get the best possible product available.\n\nResources \nKey reading \n Association of Public Health Laboratories&#32;(May 2016).&#32;\"Guidance for State Medical Cannabis Testing Programs\"&#32;(PDF).&#32;pp. 35.&#32;https:\/\/www.aphl.org\/aboutAPHL\/publications\/Documents\/EH-Guide-State-Med-Cannabis-052016.pdf . &#160; Steep Hill\n Vitale Scientific Associates\n The Werc Shop\nLicensed cultivators \nThis information is based largely on state-supplied resources and is up-to-date as of February 28, 2020.\n\nCanada \nCanada's cultivators are licensed by the federal government. The country has 43 cultivation licenses, which can be viewed on their licensed cultivators, processors, and sellers page. A variety of fees are applied to applicants, including application fees, security clearance fees, import\/export fees, and annual regulatory fees. Consult the country's Cannabis Fees Order Guide for details.\n\r\n\n\nUnited States \nAlaska:\nThe state boasts 95 Limited and 117 Standard Marijuana Cultivation Facilities. The state differentiates a \"limited\" facility as one with 500 square feet or less of grow operation space, whereas \"standard\" facilities have no such limitation.&#91;1&#93; To review the entire list of 200+ cultivation facilities, go to https:\/\/www.commerce.alaska.gov\/web\/amco\/ and look for the link \"Licenses and Applications by Status.\"\nLicensing fees for limited are $1,000, and $5,000 for standard.&#91;2&#93;\n\r\n\nArizona:\nThe government ties cultivation to dispensaries. However, Arizona state law prohibits making public a list of dispensaries, so the state's cultivators\/dispensaries are not publicly known.&#91;3&#93;\n\r\n\nArkansas:\nThe five cultivation facilities for Arkansas are&#91;4&#93;:\n\n Bold Team, LLC (Cotton Plant)\n Delta Medical Cannabis Co. (Newport)\n Natural State Medicinals Cultivation, LLC (White Hall)\n Natural State Wellness Enterprises, LLC (Newport)\n Osage Creek Cultivation, LLC (Berryville)\nAs of January 19, 2020, four of the five were up and running, with Delta Medical awaiting final inspections.&#91;5&#93;\nThe five facilities were licensed after paying a $100,000 license fee and a $500,000 performance bond.&#91;6&#93;\n\r\n\nCalifornia:\nThe state of California has approximately more than 2,100 unique cannabis adult-use and medicinal-use cultivators of provisional and annual status. As of January 1, 2019, the state no longer has the authority to issue temporary licenses, though normal adult-use and medicinal-use cultivation licenses can still be applied for.&#91;7&#93; To review the entire list of more than 850 unique cultivation businesses (note: some companies have more than one license), go to https:\/\/aca6.accela.com\/CALCANNABIS\/Cap\/CapHome.aspx?module=Licenses, select the license type, then select \"Active\" from the License Status. (Active licenses won't be older than January 1, 2018.)\nApplication and license fees vary depending on facility type. Consult the FAQ's \"How much do application\/license fees cost?\" for the latest regulatory text indicating these fees.\n\r\n\nColorado:\nThe state has more than 360 unique medical-use and more than 600 unique adult-use cultivators. To review the two lists in their entirety, go to https:\/\/www.colorado.gov\/pacific\/enforcement\/med-licensed-facilities and select the PDF or Excel file labeled \"Cultivations\" under each column.\nCultivation application and license fees vary based upon operation size. The base fee for everyone is Tier 1 (1 \u2013 1,800 plants) - $1,500.00.&#91;8&#93;\nFor cultivators who wish to expand their operations, the following is paid in addition to the Tier 1 fee&#91;8&#93;:\n\n Tier 2 (1,801 \u2013 3,600 plants) - $1,000.00\n Tier 3 (3,601 \u2013 6,000 plants) - $2,000.00\n Tier 4 (6,001 \u2013 10,200 plants) - $4,000.00\n Tier 5 (10,201 \u2013 13,800 plants) - $6,000.00\n Each additional tier of 3,600 plants over Tier 5 - $1,000.00 \n\r\n\nConnecticut:\nAccording to Connecticut's license lookup for medical marijuana producers, the four entities are licensed to cultivate in the state:\n\n Advanced Grow Labs, LLC\n Connecticut Pharmaceutical Solutions, LLC\n Curaleaf, LLC\n Theraplant, LLC\nThe state is not currently accepting new applications. However, the application fees for licenses were $25,000 for the initial applications, a $75,000 registration fee, and a $75,000 renewal fee.&#91;9&#93;\n\r\n\nDelaware:\nThe state's cultivation facilities are vertically integrated with its dispensaries, i.e., dispensaries are also cultivators. The three entities operating cultivation centers in Delaware are&#91;10&#93;&#91;11&#93;:\n\n Columbia Care, LLC (three locations)\n Compassionate Care Research Institute, Inc.\n First State Compassion Center, Inc. (two locations)\nThese compassion centers pay a $40,000 license fee ever two years.&#91;12&#93;\nThe state is not currently accepting new applications.\n\r\n\nDistrict of Columbia:\nThe District of Columbia allows eight cultivators to operate&#91;13&#93;:\n\n Abatin Wellness Center Of The District Of Columbia, LLC\n Apelles Investment Management, LLC dba Columbia Care\n District Growers, LLC\n Holistic Remedies, LLC\n Montana Apothecary, LLC dba Alternative Solutions\n Organic Wellness, LLC\n Phyto Management, LLC\n VentureForth, LLC dba Center City Cultivation\nThe state is not currently accepting new applications.\n\r\n\nFlorida:\nThe state's cultivation is vertically integrated with it its other cannabis functions, and \"medical marijuana treatment centers are the only businesses allowed to grow, process or sell\nmedical marijuana in Florida.\"&#91;14&#93; However, vertical integration may be removed as a requirement in 2020, though that progress has stalled.&#91;15&#93; The state currently has 14 medical marijuana treatment centers&#91;14&#93;:\n\n 3 Boys Farm, LLC \n Acreage Florida, Inc. dba Green Owl Pharms&#91;16&#93;\n CCF HoldCo, LLC dba Columbia Care Florida\n Curaleaf Florida, LLC dba Curaleaf\n DFMMJ Investments, LLC dba Liberty Health Sciences\n Green Thumb Industries Investments, LLC dba RiSE Dispensaries\n GrowHealthy Farms Florida, LLC dba GrowHealthy\n Harvest Health &amp; Recreation, Inc.\n Knox Management Services, LLC dba Knox Medical (Going through a name change)\n MM Enterprises, USA, LLC dba MedMen \n NuTrae, LLC dba AltMed Florida (M\u00fcV) \n Surterra Holdings, Inc. dba Surterra Wellness\n Trulieve, Inc.\n Vidacann, Ltd. \nThe state is not currently accepting new applications. Its application fee was reported to be $60,830.&#91;17&#93;\n\r\n\nHawaii:\nThe state of Hawaii allows for eight entities to grow and distribute medical marijuana, with each entity able to have two production centers and two dispensaries. Each production center is limited to a maximum of 5,000 cannabis plants. Those eight entities are&#91;18&#93;:\n\n Aloha Green Holdings, Inc. dba Aloha Green Apothecary\n Green Aloha, Ltd.\n Hawaiian Ethos, LLC\n Lau Ola, LLC dba Big Island Grown (B.I.G.) Dispensaries\n M\u0101noa Botanicals, LLC dba Noa Botanicals\n Maui Wellness Group, LLC dba Maui Grown Therapies\n Pono Life Sciences, LLC\n TCG Retro Market 1, LLC dba Cure Oahu\nThe state is not currently accepting new applications. It's application fee was $5,000, initial license fee $75,000, and license renewal fee $50,000.&#91;19&#93;\n\r\n\nIllinois:\nIllinois law allows up to 22 cultivation centers to be established in the state, with the intent being to create a center in each police district. The current cultivation centers are (some entities have centers in more than one district)&#91;20&#93;&#91;21&#93;:\n\n Ataraxia, LLC\n Bedford Grow, LLC\n Compass Ventures, Inc.\n Cresco Labs, LLC\n Curative Health Cultivation, LLC dba Columbia Care Illinois\n Effingham Medicinal Farms, LLC\n GTI Oglesby LLC and GTI Rock Island, LLC\n IESO, LLC\n Illinois Grown Medicine, LLC\n In Grown Farms, LLC\n Nature\u2019s Grace and Wellness, LLC\n PharmaCann, LLC\n Progressive Treatment Solutions, LLC\n Revolution Cannabis - Barry, LLC and Revolution Cannabis - Delavan, LLC\n Shelbyville County Community Services, Inc.\n Wellness Group Pharms, LLC\nThe state is not currently accepting new applications. Fees associated with a cultivation center include a $25,000 application fee, a $200,000 first-year license fee, and a $100,000 annual license fee afterwards.&#91;22&#93;\n\r\n\nLouisiana:\nDifficulties meeting laboratory testing requirements and acquisitions involving a grow operation have slowed down the progress of getting the state's growing operations started.&#91;23&#93;&#91;24&#93; Two growing operations are coming online in 2019, however.&#91;25&#93; Those operations are&#91;25&#93;&#91;24&#93;:\n\n GBSciences, Inc., hired by Louisiana State University, then sold to Wellcana Plus, LLC\n Ilera Holistic Healthcare, which bought Advanced Biomedics, originally hired by Southern University\n\r\n\nMaine:\nCultivation and manufacturing is vertically integrated with dispensaries. The state currently allows for eight such facilities, which are run by five entities&#91;26&#93;: \n\n Canuvo, Inc.\n Northeast Patients Group dba Wellness Connection of Maine (four locations)\n Primary Organic Therapy, Inc. dba Maine Organic Therapy\n Remedy Compassion Center, Inc. dba CuraLeaf Auburn\n Safe Alternatives\nApplications don't currently appear to be accepted. Registration fees were $12,000, and a moving fee of $4,000 was also required.&#91;27&#93;\n\r\n\nMaryland:\nThe state does not require vertical integration among its growers, dispensaries, and producers, but many growers may also be integrated with dispensaries, etc. Maryland currently has 14 licensed growers&#91;28&#93;:\n\n Curio Cultivation, LLC \n Doctors Orders Maryland, LLC\n ForwardGro, LLC \n Freestate Wellness, LLC\n Green Leaf Medical, LLC\n Grow West MD, LLC \n Harvest of Maryland Cultivation, LLC\n HMS Health, LLC \n Holistic Industries, Inc.\n Kind Therapeutics USA, LLC\n Maryland Compassionate Care and Wellness, LLC dba as Grassroots Cannabis\n MaryMed, LLC\n Shore Natural Rx, LLC\n SunMed Growers LLC\n Temescal Wellness\nThe state opened the application process again for growers and processors, with applications being accepted from March 25 to May 24, 2019. (Seeking to add four new growers and 10 new processors.) The state requires a $2,000 application fee&#91;29&#93; and a $250,000 two-year license fee.&#91;30&#93; As of February 2020, the announcement of the new approved growers and processors was delayed due to an investigation into the fairness of the approval process.&#91;31&#93;\n\r\n\nMassachusetts:\nThe state does not require vertical integration among its growers, dispensaries, and producers, but many growers may also be integrated with dispensaries, etc. Massachusetts currently has 26 licensed cultivators&#91;32&#93;:\n\n Alternative Therapies Group, Inc.\n Berkshire Roots, Inc.\n Caregiver-Patient Connection\n Commcan, Inc.\n Cultivate Holdings, LLC\n Curaleaf Massachusetts, Inc.\n Garden Remedies, Inc.\n Good Chemistry of Massachusetts, Inc.\n Green Lady Dispensary, Inc.\n Hope Heal Health, Inc.\n In Good Health, Inc.\n I.N.S.A., Inc.\n M3 Ventures, Inc.\n Mass Alternative Care, Inc.\n Mayflower Medicinals, Inc.\n Nature\u2019s Remedy of Massachusetts, Inc.\n New England Treatment Access, LLC\n Northeast Alternatives, Inc.\n Nova Farms, LLC\n Patriot Care Corp.\n Revolutionary Clinics II, Inc.\n RISE Holdings, Inc.\n Sanctuary Medicinals, Inc.\n SIRA Naturals, Inc.\n Temescal Wellness of Massachusetts Holdings, LLC\n Theory Wellness, Inc.\nApplication and license fees vary based on how many plants are to be grown in the cultivation facility. Refer to the Cannabis Control Commission's guidance document \"Guidance for Application and License Fees\" for details.\n\r\n\nMichigan:\nThe state does not require vertical integration among its growers, dispensaries, and producers, but many growers may also be integrated with dispensaries, etc. Michigan currently has 87 licensed cultivators&#91;33&#93;:\n\n 13774 Buena Vista, LLC\n 3843 Euclid, LLC \n 818 Terminal Road, LLC\n A &amp; H Partners, LLC\n A2BG, LLC\n Adams Family Farms, LLC\n AEY Capital, LLC\n Alvarez Cultivation, LLC\n Arbor Farm I, LLC\n Attitude Wellness, LLC\n Aunt Sparkie's, Inc.\n Baudville, Inc.\n BlueSol Biomedical, LLC\n Cannrose, Inc.\n Center Creek, LLC\n Central Coast Horticultural, LLC\n Choice Labs, LLC\n Connorberry Farms, LLC\n Country Boy Farms, LLC\n CRG Buds, LLC\n DCAD, LLC\n Detroit Bud Company, Inc.\n DJR Michigan Properties, LLC\n DLG &amp; A $20,000 application fee was due for anyone who applied.&#91;36&#93;\n\r\n\nMissouri:\nAfter the first wave of approvals in December 2019, the state has 36 unique businesses licensed to cultivate cannabis in the state. To view the list of cultivation facilities, go the licensed facilities page for the state and download the related Excel sheet.\nLicensing application fees were $10,000.&#91;37&#93; Applications for cultivation, testing, manufacturing, and dispensary facilities are currently not being accepted.\n\r\n\nMontana:\nThe medical marijuana program in the state is in a bit of disarray. As Michigan-based New Leaf Cannabis Consulting puts it&#91;38&#93;: \n\nVoters re-approved medical cannabis in the state in Nov. 2016. Dispensaries were supposed to not open until June 2017, but a Montana court ruled that they may reopen immediately. Montana used to have an established medical cannabis dispensary program, but a court ruling upholding a severe state law dismantled the dispensaries, by limiting the maximum number of patients to 3; that portion of the law is now repealed.\nAs of mid-July 2019, the program had finally bounced back to a patient base similar to pre-2011 levels.&#91;39&#93; The state's language is a bit confusing, but it appears that \"Providers\" are cultivators, and if that is the case, the state currently has 270 licenses issued for cultivators. Visit the state's program website and click on \"Licensed Providers in Complia.\"\n\r\n\nNevada:\nThe current number and details of the state's licensed cultivators are unknown. Per an inquiry and a form letter emailed from the Marijuana Enforcement Division of Nevada, \"the state is only permitted to release information on open dispensaries,\" and does not release information on current licensed cultivators. However, a list of provisional certificates awarded in November 2014 can still be found on their site, though many of the names are redacted due to confidentiality laws in the state.\nLicensing fees for cultivation facilities differ based on product. Recreational marijuana cultivation has an initial $30,000 licensing fee, with renewal costs at $10,000. Medical marijuana cultivation has an initial $3,000 license, with renewal costs at $1,000.&#91;40&#93;\n\r\n\nNew Hampshire:\nThe state vertically integrates cultivation and dispensation of medical cannabis into alternative treatment centers, with the state currently allowing for five locations run by three entities&#91;41&#93;:\n\n Prime Alternative Treatment Centers of NH, Inc.\n Sanctuary ATC\n Temescal Wellness, Inc. (two locations)\nThe state doesn't appear to be accepting new applications, and it's not clear what fees applicants had to pay.\n\r\n\nNew Jersey:\nThe state vertically integrates cultivation and dispensation of medical cannabis into alternative treatment centers, with the state currently allowing for nine locations run by seven entities&#91;41&#93;:\n\n Breakwater Alternative Treatment Center Corp.\n CuraLeaf NJ, Inc.\n Compassionate Care Foundation, Inc.\n Garden State Dispensary\n Greenleaf Compassion Center\n Harmony Dispensary\n Rise\nAn application period occurred in July 2018 to grant six more licenses. In December 2018, six additional providers were invited to proceed with the application process, though in February 2019 five appeals were filed by rejected applicants and an existing alternative treatment center in regards to the selected six. Due to the litigation, only one those six providers\u2014Rise\u2014has become fully licensed and operational.&#91;42&#93;&#91;43&#93;&#91;44&#93; As of February 2020, more lawsuits have delayed final approvals even further, with no clear conclusion in site.&#91;44&#93;\n\r\n\nNew Mexico:\nNew Mexico vertically integrates cultivation and distribution. The state calls such licensed entities \"licensed non-profit producers\" (LNPPs), of which 107 locations are operational.&#91;45&#93; (Go here to see the full list.)\nThe state is not accepting additional applications at this time. Initial application fee was $10,000, with a license fee of \"thirty thousand dollars ($30,000) for the first 150 cannabis plants to be possessed by the non-profit producer, and ten thousand dollars ($10,000) for each additional quantity of 50 plants thereafter to be possessed, up to a maximum collective total of 450 cannabis plants.\"&#91;46&#93;\n\r\n\nNew York:\nThe state vertically integrates cultivation and dispensation of medical cannabis into registered organizations. Each registered organization can have one cultivation facility and up to four dispensaries. Those organizations are&#91;47&#93;:\n\n Citivia Medical, LLC\n Columbia Care NY, LLC\n Curaleaf NY, LLC\n Etain, LLC\n Fiorello Pharmaceuticals, Inc. dba FP Wellness\n MedMen, Inc.\n NYCANNA, LLC dba The Botanist or Acreage NY\n PharmaCann of New York, LLC\n Vireo Health of New York, LLC\n Valley Agriceuticals, LLC dba Remedy-NY\n Vireo Health of New York, LLC\nApplications are not currently being accepted. Applications fee was $10,000, licensing fee $200,000.&#91;48&#93;\n\r\n\nNorth Dakota:\nThe state approved two cultivation sites in 2018 for its medical marijuana program&#91;49&#93;:\n\n GR Vending ND, LLC dba Grassroots Cannabis\n Pure Dakota, LLC\nAdditional cultivation applications don't appear to be accepted. An initial $5,000 application fee was required, and a $110,000 certification fee for a two-year license.&#91;50&#93;\n\r\n\nOhio:\nThe state of Ohio approved 30 total cultivator licenses, 17 for Level I and 13 for Level II. They are&#91;51&#93;:\n\n Agri-Med Ohio, LLC\n Ancient Roots, LLC\n Ascension BioMedical, LLC\n AT-CPC of Ohio, LLC\n Buckeye Relief, LLC\n Certified Cultivators\n Columbia Care OH, LLC\n Cresco Labs Ohio, LLC\n FarmacetuicalRX, LLC\n Farkas Farms, LLC\n Fire Rock Ltd.\n FN Group Holdings, LLC\n Galenas, LLC\n Greenleaf Gardens\n Grow Ohio Pharmaceuticals, LLC\n Harvest Grows, LLC\n Hemma, LLC\n Mother Grows Best, LLC\n OhiGrow, LLC\n Ohio Clean Leaf, LLC\n Ohio Grown Therapies, LLC\n OPC Cultivation, LLC\n Paragon Development Group, LLC\n Parma Wellness Center, LLC\n PharmaCann Ohio, LLC\n Pure OH, LLC\n Pure Ohio Wellness, LLC\n Riviera Creek Holdings, LLC\n Standard Wellness Company, LLC\n Terradiol Ohio, LLC (may get revoked&#91;52&#93;\nThe state is not currently accepting applications. Application fees were $20,000 for Level I and $2,000 for Level II cultivators, with initial license fees of $180,000 and $18,000 respectively, and annual renewal fees of $200,000 and $20,000 respectively. (Level I permitted to 25,000 square feet initially, Level II to 3,000 square feet initially.)&#91;51&#93;\n\r\n\nOklahoma:\nIn April 2019, the state released a document containing 118 pages of cannabis cultivators for its medical marijuana program. Consult the \"List of Licensed Businesses\" to view the entire list. Application\/license fee is $2,500 annually.&#91;53&#93;\n\r\n\nOregon\nOregon boasts 1,162 recreational cannabis cultivation licenses across its program. (Medical cannabis growers are designated by an Oregon Medical Marijuana Program.&#91;54&#93;) To view the list of cultivators, go here and choose the PDF or Excel document titled \"Approved Marijuana Licenses.\" \nApplication fee is $250, license fee varies depending license type ($100\u2013$5,750).&#91;55&#93;\n\r\n\nPennsylvania:\nThe state initially introduced 12 grower-processor licenses with Phase I of its program.&#91;56&#93; In 2018, the state issued 13 additional permits to grower-processors&#91;57&#93;, taking the total to the allowed-for 25. They are:\n\n AES Compassionate Care, LLC dba Grassroots Cannabis\n Agri-Kind, LLC\n AGRiMED Industries of PA, LLC dba AGRiMED Ward Site\n Calypso Enterprises, LLC\n Cresco Yeltrah, LLC dba Jefferson County Grower\/Processor Facility\n DocHouse, LLC\n FarmaceuticalRx, LLC\n Franklin Labs, LLC\n Green Leaf Medicals, LLC\n GTI Pennsylvania, LLC dba GTI Danville Grow\/Process\n Hanging Gardens, LLC dba Iron Street\n Holistic Farms, LLC\n Ilera Healthcare, LLC\n INSA, LLC\n Maitri Genetics, LLC\n Parea BioSciences, LLC\n PennAlt Organics, Inc. dba Penn Health's Cultivation Facility\n Pennsylvania Medical Solutions, LLC\n PharmaCann Penn Plant, LLC\n Pier Cove, LLC dba Justice Grown Cultivation and Processing Center\n Prime Wellness of Pennsylvania, LLC\n PurePenn, LLC\n Standard Farms, LLC (Acquired by TILT Holdings, Inc. in January 2019&#91;58&#93;)\n Terrapin Investment Fund 1, LLC dba Terrapin Care Station\n Whole Plants, LLC dba WP Health Foundry\nApplications are currently not being accepted. Prior applicants paid a $10,000 application fee and $200,000 permit fee.&#91;57&#93;\n\r\n\nRhode Island:\nThe state has given licenses to 52 cultivators, with 21 additional licenses pending final licensing inspection. Consult the state's approval page for the full list. The application process is currently closed. Prior applicants were required to pay a $5,000 application fee. Annual license fees vary based upon the class (grow operation size) license: Micro at $5,000, Class A at $20,000, Class B at $35,000, Class C at $50,000, and Class D at $80,000.&#91;59&#93;\n\r\n\nUtah:\nThe state handed out eight of its 10 cultivator licenses in 2019. See the state's cannabis program site for details. Those eight cultivators are:\n\n Dragonfly Greenhouse, LLC\n Harvest of Utah, LLC\n Oakbridge Greenhouse and Floral, Inc.\n Standard Wellness Utah, LLC\n True North of Utah, LLC\n Tryke Companies Utah, LLC\n Wholesome Ag., LLC\n Zion Cultivars, LLC\nApplications are currently not being accepted by the state. The original application fee was $2,500, with an additional $51.50 for a background check. Approved licensees pay $100,000 for the first-year license.&#91;60&#93;\n\r\n\nVermont:\nVermont vertically integrates cultivation and distribution and refers to licensed entities as \"dispensaries.\" The state has issued five dispensary registration certificates&#91;61&#93;:\n\n Champlain Valley Dispensary, Inc. dba as Champlain Valley Dispensary\n Champlain Valley Dispensary, Inc. dba as Southern Vermont Wellness\n FWR, Inc. dba Grassroots Vermont\n Phytoscience Institute, LLC dba PhytoCare Vermont\n Vermont Patients Alliance, Inc.\nThe state has said it plans on opening the application process to a sixth dispensary once patient count reaches 7000 (which could happen in 2020).&#91;61&#93; Application fees were $2,500 and license fees set at $20,000. Annual renewal fee is $30,000.&#91;62&#93;\n\r\n\nWashington:\nThe state has more than 1,050 active production licenses issued. To view the entire list, go here, export the list, and sort out the production facilities. The state is not accepting new applications at this time. Application fees were $250, with an annual $1,480 annual license fee for producers.&#91;63&#93;\n\r\n\nWest Virginia:\n\n The state is still working on developing its medical cannabis program due to unanticipated delays&#91;64&#93;, particularly with finding banking solutions for the program.&#91;65&#93; The Bureau for Public Health indicates that it plans on issuing no more than 10 permits for cultivators. The initial application fee will be $5,000 and the permit fee $50,000.&#91;66&#93; The application period should open sometime in 2019.&#91;65&#93; The state ceased accepting application for cultivators on February 18, 2020.&#91;64&#93;\nTesting labs and pricing info \nCanada \nThe following are licensed cannabis testing labs, as reported by Health Canada.&#91;67&#93; Note that some of these laboratories are not stand-alone laboratories accepting samples but rather in-house labs testing for R&amp;D or manufacturing programs.\n\r\n\nAlberta\n\n AGAT Laboratories Ltd.\n Bio-Chem Consulting Services (1980) Ltd.\n Caro Analytical Services Ltd.\n Drug Development and Innovation Centre\n InnoTech Alberta, Inc.\n Intertek Testing Services (ITS) Canada Ltd.\n Keystone Labs, Inc.\n Labs-Mart, Inc.\n Olds Softgels, Inc.\n PBR Laboratories, Inc.\n Quality Analytical Services Ltd.\n Radient Technologies, Inc.\n SGS Canada, Inc.\n\r\n\nBritish Columbia\n\n Activation Laboratories Ltd.\n AGAT Laboratories Ltd.\n Anandia Laboratories, Inc.\n Avalite Sciences, Inc.\n Cannevert Therapeutics Ltd.\n Caro Analytical Services Ltd.\n Centre for Applied Research and Innovation\n Chemia Analytics, Inc.\n Drug Analysis Service\n Green Sky Laboratories Corp.\n Intertek Testing Services (ITS) Canada Ltd.\n Labs-Mart, Inc.\n M.B. id=\"rdp-ebb-globalWrapper\">\n\t\t<div id=\"rdp-ebb-column-content\">\n\t\t\t<div id=\"rdp-ebb-content\" class=\"mw-body\" role=\"main\">\n\t\t\t\t<a id=\"rdp-ebb-top\"><\/a>\n\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t<h1 id=\"rdp-ebb-firstHeading\" class=\"firstHeading\" lang=\"en\">RefWork:Past, Present, and Future of Cannabis Laboratory Testing and Regulation in the United States\/Final thoughts and resources<\/h1>\n\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t<div id=\"rdp-ebb-bodyContent\" class=\"mw-body-content\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n\n\t\t\t\t\t<!-- start content -->\n\t\t\t\t\t<div id=\"rdp-ebb-mw-content-text\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\" class=\"mw-content-ltr\"><p>This last section of the guide provides closing thoughts to tie together what was previously discussed. It also provides a directory of cannabis testing, standards, etc. resources for readers wanting to learn more.\n<\/p>\n<div align=\"center\">-----Return to <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=RefWork:Past,_Present,_and_Future_of_Cannabis_Laboratory_Testing_and_Regulation_in_the_United_States\" title=\"RefWork:Past, Present, and Future of Cannabis Laboratory Testing and Regulation in the United States\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"6f7f2fc7206d8a9a7e22a97bf66c5127\">the beginning<\/a> of this guide-----<\/div>\n\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"6._Final_thoughts\">6. Final thoughts<\/span><\/h2>\n<div class=\"floatright\"><a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=File:LAB_COURSE_IN_CHROMATOGRAPHY.jpg\" class=\"image wiki-link\" data-key=\"4628d7739f4218cc5e3b68e17df0bd84\"><img alt=\"LAB COURSE IN CHROMATOGRAPHY.jpg\" src=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/images\/thumb\/5\/53\/LAB_COURSE_IN_CHROMATOGRAPHY.jpg\/300px-LAB_COURSE_IN_CHROMATOGRAPHY.jpg\" style=\"width: 100%;max-width: 400px;height: auto;\" \/><\/a><\/div> This guide has attempted to provide insight into various aspects of the current status of <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Laboratory\" title=\"Laboratory\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"ed14e6a67b4b14ad2c190c28455725f6\">laboratory<\/a> testing of <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Cannabis\" title=\"Cannabis\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"a70b76268930d795518ff1f98d7e500d\">cannabis<\/a> in the U.S. By extension, it has required a closer look at many non-testing or tangentially related aspects of cannabis, including history, regulations, standards, methods, equipment, and software. The guide has also attempted to look at the potential future of testing, a more difficult feat that has required inspection of\u2014and speculation on\u2014a mix of statistics and politics, as well as government and social policy and how they may all affect the future of cannabis testing. We learned that many point fingers at the U.S. federal government for being responsible for several cannabis-related issues, including lack of clear government support for cannabis research, lack of standardization of testing and analysis methods for said research, and wavering policy that remains inconsistent at best. At root is the fact that the federal government maintains cannabis (and its constituents) as a <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Controlled_Substances_Act#Schedule_of_controlled_substances\" title=\"Controlled Substances Act\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"4b8a6179508959a4f503c9a4dba4224a\">Schedule I<\/a> drug, by extension declaring that it has no respectable medical use. This and related decisions have slowed down the academic study of cannabis (at least in the U.S.), including its analysis, quality testing, and research and use as a medical treatment. The development, implementation, and reassessment of <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Cannabis_cultivation\" title=\"Cannabis cultivation\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"2a93fc4d018f9aaacd8e9024a56eaa13\">cultivation<\/a> and testing standards and methods have largely been piecemeal; additionally, those efforts have been enacted in an environment where, despite the legal status in a state, fear that the federal government will inevitably intervene slows progress even further.\n<p>Despite these barriers, the speed at which U.S. states have adopted some form of legalization of cannabis has pushed scientists and researchers to collaborate and improve standards and methods. Necessity continues to be the mother of invention, driving those in the industry to adapt or perish in a difficult, inconsistent market. State officials are teaming up at industry conferences and sharing ideas. Non-profit organizations are joining forces with major standards agencies to expand and improve good laboratory practices. Researchers\u2014whether on their own or with the help of others internationally\u2014are learning more about the various <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Cannabinoid\" title=\"Cannabinoid\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"c224c3041748677fcdce5b5209900b7b\">cannabinoids<\/a> and their interaction with <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Terpene\" title=\"Terpene\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"6bcbb95d582c08073101e9c4cfc91931\">terpenes<\/a>, driving new insight into potential therapeutic remedies. Overall public perception about <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Cannabis_(drug)\" title=\"Cannabis (drug)\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"6500790ffdd84957d4b055c47e48efca\">marijuana<\/a> consumption and use is gradually shifting towards a positive light, even when so little is still understood about the long-term ramifications of its use. Commercial interests are taking notice, and so are international treaty makers. All of this adds up to forward momentum in the cannabis industry, with warts and all.\n<\/p><p>Many factors will affect the future of cannabis regulation, testing, and research; in the process, we're certain to see both ups and downs as political and social climates continue to change. However, as marijuana consumption and <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Hemp\" title=\"Hemp\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"c23e30b6cf1df54f1dc338492c9f9da2\">hemp<\/a>-based manufacturing methods continue to see expanded support, consumers and manufacturers, as well as all those involved in between, will always clamor for a safer product that is \"as advertised.\" Laboratory analysis will play an important role in that effort, whether it's in the medical research lab, the quality control lab, or the manufacturer's lab. It will be imperative for all interested parties to further work together to ensure methods are sound and standardized in a realistic and beneficial way to ensure that in the end consumers will get the best possible product available.\n<\/p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Resources\">Resources<\/span><\/h2>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Key_reading\">Key largely on state-supplied resources and is up-to-date as of February 28, 2020.\n<\/p>\n<h4><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Canada\">Canada<\/span><\/h4>\n<p>Canada's cultivators are licensed by the federal government. The country has 43 cultivation licenses, which can be viewed on their <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"external_link\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/www.canada.ca\/en\/health-canada\/services\/drugs-medication\/cannabis\/industry-licensees-applicants\/licensed-cultivators-processors-sellers.html\">licensed cultivators, processors, and sellers page<\/a>. A variety of fees are applied to applicants, including application fees, security clearance fees, import\/export fees, and annual regulatory fees. Consult the country's <i><a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"external_link\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/www.canada.ca\/en\/health-canada\/services\/publications\/drugs-health-products\/cannabis-fees-order.html\">Cannabis Fees Order Guide<\/a><\/i> for details.\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p>\n<h4><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"United_States\">United States<\/span><\/h4>\n<p><b>Alaska<\/b>:\n<\/p><p>The state boasts 95 Limited and 117 Standard Marijuana Cultivation Facilities. The state differentiates a \"limited\" facility as one with 500 square feet or less of grow operation space, whereas \"standard\" facilities have no such limitation.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-SummersCult16_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-SummersCult16-1\">&#91;1&#93;<\/a><\/sup> To review the entire list of 200+ cultivation facilities, go to <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"external_link\" class=\"external free\" href=\"https:\/\/www.commerce.alaska.gov\/web\/amco\/\">https:\/\/www.commerce.alaska.gov\/web\/amco\/<\/a> and look for the link \"Licenses and Applications by Status.\"\n<\/p><p>Licensing fees for limited are $1,000, and $5,000 for standard.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-AMCOMariLic_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-AMCOMariLic-2\">&#91;2&#93;<\/a><\/sup>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<b>Arizona<\/b>:\n<\/p><p>The government ties cultivation to dispensaries. However, Arizona state law prohibits making public a list of dispensaries, so the state's cultivators\/dispensaries are not publicly known.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-AZDHSFAQsDisp_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-AZDHSFAQsDisp-3\">&#91;3&#93;<\/a><\/sup>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<b>Arkansas<\/b>:\n<\/p><p>The five cultivation facilities for Arkansas are<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-FieldBuild19_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-FieldBuild19-4\">&#91;4&#93;<\/a><\/sup>:\n<\/p>\n<ul><li> Bold Team, LLC (Cotton Plant)<\/li>\n<li> Delta Medical Cannabis Co. (Newport)<\/li>\n<li> Natural State Medicinals Cultivation, LLC (White Hall)<\/li>\n<li> Natural State Wellness Enterprises, LLC (Newport)<\/li>\n<li> Osage Creek Cultivation, LLC (Berryville)<\/li><\/ul>\n<p>As of January 19, 2020, four of the five were up and running, with Delta Medical awaiting final inspections.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-FieldLagging20_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-FieldLagging20-5\">&#91;5&#93;<\/a><\/sup>\n<\/p><p>The five facilities were licensed after paying a $100,000 license fee and a $500,000 performance bond.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-GrabensteinArk18_6-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-GrabensteinArk18-6\">&#91;6&#93;<\/a><\/sup>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<b>California<\/b>:\n<\/p><p>The state of California has approximately more than 2,100 unique cannabis adult-use and medicinal-use cultivators of provisional and annual status. As of January 1, 2019, the state no longer has the authority to issue temporary licenses, though normal adult-use and medicinal-use cultivation licenses can still be applied for.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-CalCanNotice19_7-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-CalCanNotice19-7\">&#91;7&#93;<\/a><\/sup> To review the entire list of more than 850 unique cultivation businesses (note: some companies have more than one license), go to <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"external_link\" class=\"external free\" href=\"https:\/\/aca6.accela.com\/CALCANNABIS\/Cap\/CapHome.aspx?module=Licenses\">https:\/\/aca6.accela.com\/CALCANNABIS\/Cap\/CapHome.aspx?module=Licenses<\/a>, select the license type, then select \"Active\" from the License Status. (Active licenses won't be older than January 1, 2018.)\n<\/p><p>Application and license fees vary depending on facility type. Consult <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"external_link\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/cannabis.ca.gov\/faqs\/\">the FAQ's<\/a> \"How much do application\/license fees cost?\" for the latest regulatory text indicating these fees.\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<b>Colorado<\/b>:\n<\/p><p>The state has more than 360 unique medical-use and more than 600 unique adult-use cultivators. To review the two lists in their entirety, go to <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"external_link\" class=\"external free\" href=\"https:\/\/www.colorado.gov\/pacific\/enforcement\/med-licensed-facilities\">https:\/\/www.colorado.gov\/pacific\/enforcement\/med-licensed-facilities<\/a> and select the PDF or Excel file labeled \"Cultivations\" under each column.\n<\/p><p>Cultivation application and license fees vary based upon operation size. The base fee for everyone is Tier 1 (1 \u2013 1,800 plants) - $1,500.00.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-ColRetail17_8-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ColRetail17-8\">&#91;8&#93;<\/a><\/sup>\n<\/p><p>For cultivators who wish to expand their operations, the following is paid in addition to the Tier 1 fee<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-ColRetail17_8-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ColRetail17-8\">&#91;8&#93;<\/a><\/sup>:\n<\/p>\n<ul><li> Tier 2 (1,801 \u2013 3,600 plants) - $1,000.00<\/li>\n<li> Tier 3 (3,601 \u2013 6,000 plants) - $2,000.00<\/li>\n<li> Tier 4 (6,001 \u2013 10,200 plants) - $4,000.00<\/li>\n<li> Tier 5 (10,201 \u2013 13,800 plants) - $6,000.00<\/li>\n<li> Each additional tier of 3,600 plants over Tier 5 - $1,000.00 <\/li><\/ul>\n<p><br \/>\n<b>Connecticut<\/b>:\n<\/p><p>According to Connecticut's <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"external_link\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/www.elicense.ct.gov\/Lookup\/LicenseLookup.aspx\">license lookup<\/a> for medical marijuana producers, the four entities are licensed to cultivate in the state:\n<\/p>\n<ul><li> <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"external_link\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/advancedgrowlabs.com\/\">Advanced Grow Labs, LLC<\/a><\/li>\n<li> <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"external_link\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/www.ctpharma.com\/\">Connecticut Pharmaceutical Solutions, LLC<\/a><\/li>\n<li> <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"external_link\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/ct.curaleaf.com\/\">Curaleaf, LLC<\/a><\/li>\n<li> <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"external_link\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/www.theraplant.com\/\">Theraplant, LLC<\/a><\/li><\/ul>\n<p>The state is not currently accepting new applications. However, the application fees for licenses were $25,000 for the initial applications, a $75,000 registration fee, and a $75,000 renewal fee.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-DCPMedical_9-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-DCPMedical-9\">&#91;9&#93;<\/a><\/sup>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<b>Delaware<\/b>:\n<\/p><p>The state's cultivation facilities are vertically integrated with its dispensaries, i.e., dispensaries are also cultivators. The three entities operating cultivation centers in Delaware are<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-FishmanSecond17_10-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-FishmanSecond17-10\">&#91;10&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-DelaOpenCompass_11-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-DelaOpenCompass-11\">&#91;11&#93;<\/a><\/sup>:\n<\/p>\n<ul><li> <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"external_link\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/col-care.com\/delaware\/\">Columbia Care, LLC<\/a> (three locations)<\/li>\n<li> <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"external_link\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/freshdelaware.com\/\">Compassionate Care Research Institute, Inc.<\/a><\/li>\n<li> <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"external_link\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/www.firststatecompassion.com\/\">First State Compassion Center, Inc.<\/a> (two locations)<\/li><\/ul>\n<p>These compassion centers pay a $40,000 license fee ever two years.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-DHSSDela16_12-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-DHSSDela16-12\">&#91;12&#93;<\/a><\/sup>\n<\/p><p>The state is not currently accepting new applications.\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<b>District of Columbia<\/b>:\n<\/p><p>The District of Columbia allows eight cultivators to operate<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-DCHMed19_13-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-DCHMed19-13\">&#91;13&#93;<\/a><\/sup>:\n<\/p>\n<ul><li> Abatin Wellness Center Of The District Of Columbia, LLC<\/li>\n<li> <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"external_link\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/col-care.com\/\">Apelles Investment Management, LLC dba Columbia Care<\/a><\/li>\n<li> <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"external_link\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/www.districtgrowers.com\/our-mission\">District Growers, LLC<\/a><\/li>\n<li> <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"external_link\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/www.holisticindustries.com\/\">Holistic Remedies, LLC<\/a><\/li>\n<li> Montana Apothecary, LLC dba Alternative Solutions<\/li>\n<li> Organic Wellness, LLC<\/li>\n<li> <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"external_link\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/www.districtcannabis.us\/\">Phyto Management, LLC<\/a><\/li>\n<li> VentureForth, LLC dba Center City Cultivation<\/li><\/ul>\n<p>The state is not currently accepting new applications.\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<b>Florida<\/b>:\n<\/p><p>The state's cultivation is vertically integrated with it its other cannabis functions, and \"medical marijuana treatment centers are the only businesses allowed to grow, process or sell\nmedical marijuana in Florida.\"<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-OMMUUpdate19-4_14-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-OMMUUpdate19-4-14\">&#91;14&#93;<\/a><\/sup> However, vertical integration may be removed as a requirement in 2020, though that progress has stalled.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-GrossFlorida20_15-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-GrossFlorida20-15\">&#91;15&#93;<\/a><\/sup> The state currently has 14 medical marijuana treatment centers<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-OMMUUpdate19-4_14-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-OMMUUpdate19-4-14\">&#91;14&#93;<\/a><\/sup>:\n<\/p>\n<ul><li> <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"external_link\" assessment\" fee, which is not clear in cost (varies from $10,000 to $66,000).<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-DLRAWhatWill_34-0\" class=\"reference\"><a id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-MDHMedicalCannManu_35-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-MDHMedicalCannManu-35\">&#91;35&#93;<\/a><\/sup>:\n<\/p>\n<ul><li> <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"external_link\" href=\"http:\/\/minnesotamedicalsolutions.com\/\">Minnesota Medical Solutions, LLC<\/a><\/li><\/ul>\n<p>Further applications are not being accepted at this time. A $20,000 application fee was due for anyone who applied.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-MDHMedicalCann_36-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-MDHMedicalCann-36\">&#91;36&#93;<\/a><\/sup>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<b>Missouri<\/b>:\n<\/p><p>After the first wave of approvals in December 2019, the state has 36 unique businesses licensed to cultivate cannabis in the state. To view the list of cultivation facilities, go the <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"external_link\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/health.mo.gov\/safety\/medical-marijuana\/licensed-facilities.php\">licensed facilities<\/a> page for the state and download the related Excel sheet.\n<\/p><p>Licensing application fees were $10,000.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-HolmanSoWhat19_37-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-HolmanSoWhat19-37\">&#91;37&#93;<\/a><\/sup> Applications for cultivation, testing, manufacturing, and dispensary facilities are currently not being accepted.\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<b>Montana<\/b>:\n<\/p><p>The medical marijuana program in the state is in a bit of disarray. As Michigan-based New Leaf Cannabis Consulting puts it<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-LowryMontana18_38-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-LowryMontana18-38\">&#91;38&#93;<\/a><\/sup>: \n<\/p>\n<blockquote>Voters re-approved medical cannabis in the state in Nov. 2016. Dispensaries were supposed to not open until June 2017, but a Montana court ruled that they may reopen immediately. Montana used to have an established medical cannabis dispensary program, but a court ruling upholding a severe state law dismantled the dispensaries, by limiting the maximum number of patients to 3; that portion of the law is now repealed.<\/blockquote>\n<p>As of mid-July 2019, the program had finally bounced back to a patient base similar to pre-2011 levels.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-LevensonMontana19_39-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-LevensonMontana19-39\">&#91;39&#93;<\/a><\/sup> The state's language is a bit confusing, but it appears that \"Providers\" are cultivators, and if that is the case, the state currently has 270 licenses issued for cultivators. Visit the state's <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"external_link\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/dphhs.mt.gov\/marijuana\">program website<\/a> and click on \"Licensed Providers in Complia.\"\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<b>Nevada<\/b>:\n<\/p><p>The current number and details of the state's licensed cultivators are unknown. Per an inquiry and a form letter emailed from the Marijuana Enforcement Division of Nevada, \"the state is only permitted to release information on open dispensaries,\" and does not release information on current licensed cultivators. However, a list of provisional certificates awarded in November 2014 can still be found <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"external_link\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/tax.nv.gov\/uploadedFiles\/dpbhnvgov\/content\/Reg\/MedMarijuana\/cultivationscoresrankings12-21-15.pdf\">on their site<\/a>, though many of the names are redacted due to confidentiality laws in the state.\n<\/p><p>Licensing fees for cultivation facilities differ based on product. Recreational marijuana cultivation has an initial $30,000 licensing fee, with renewal costs at $10,000. Medical marijuana cultivation has an initial $3,000 license, with renewal costs at $1,000.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-DoTMari_40-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-DoTMari-40\">&#91;40&#93;<\/a><\/sup>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<b>New Hampshire<\/b>:\n<\/p><p>The state vertically integrates cultivation and dispensation of medical cannabis into alternative treatment centers, with the state currently allowing for five locations run by three entities<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-DHHSAltern_41-0\" class=\"reference\"><a accepting new applications, and it's not clear what fees applicants had to pay.\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<b>New Jersey<\/b>:\n<\/p><p>The state vertically integrates cultivation and dispensation of medical Due to the litigation, only one those six providers\u2014Rise\u2014has become fully licensed and operational.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-DHHSUpdateOn_42-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-DHHSUpdateOn-42\">&#91;42&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-LivioTheseWeed19_43-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-LivioTheseWeed19-43\">&#91;43&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-HooverNew2020_44-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-HooverNew2020-44\">&#91;44&#93;<\/a><\/sup> As of February 2020, more lawsuits have delayed final approvals even further, with no clear conclusion in site.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-HooverNew2020_44-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-HooverNew2020-44\">&#91;44&#93;<\/a><\/sup>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<b>New Mexico<\/b>:\n<\/p><p>New Mexico vertically integrates cultivation and distribution. Annual license fees vary based upon the class (grow operation size) license: Micro at $5,000, Class A at $20,000, Class B at $35,000, Class C at $50,000, and Class D at $80,000.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-230-RICR-80-5-1_59-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-230-RICR-80-5-1-59\">&#91;59&#93;<\/a><\/sup>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<b>Utah<\/b>:\n<\/p><p>The state handed out eight of its 10 cultivator licenses in 2019. See the state's <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"external_link\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/medicalcannabis.utah.gov\/production\/cultivators\/\">cannabis program site<\/a> for details. Those eight cultivators are:\n<\/p>\n<ul><li> Dragonfly Greenhouse, LLC<\/li>\n<li> <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"external_link\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/www.harvesthoc.com\/\">Harvest of Utah, LLC<\/a><\/li>\n<li> <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"external_link\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http:\/\/oakbridgegreenhouse.com\/\">Oakbridge Greenhouse and Floral, Inc.<\/a><\/li>\n<li> <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"external_link\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/www.standardwellness.com\/\">Standard Wellness Utah, LLC<\/a><\/li>\n<li> True North of Utah, LLC<\/li>\n<li> <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"external_link\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/trykecompanies.com\/\">Tryke Companies Utah, LLC<\/a><\/li>\n<li> Wholesome Ag., LLC<\/li>\n<li> Zion Cultivars, LLC<\/li><\/ul>\n<p>Applications are currently not being accepted by the state. The original application fee was $2,500, with an additional $51.50 for a background check. Approved licensees pay $100,000 for the first-year license.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-FloresState19_60-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-FloresState19-60\">&#91;60&#93;<\/a><\/sup>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<b>Vermont<\/b>:\n<\/p><p>Vermont vertically integrates cultivation and distribution and refers to licensed entities as \"dispensaries.\" The state has issued five dispensary registration certificates<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-DPSMRRegDisp_61-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-DPSMRRegDisp-61\">&#91;61&#93;<\/a><\/sup>:\n<\/p>\n<ul><li> <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"external_link\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/www.cvdvt.org\/\">Champlain Valley Dispensary, Inc. dba as Champlain Valley Dispensary<\/a><\/li>\n<li> <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"external_link\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/www.cvdvt.org\/\">Champlain Valley Dispensary, Inc. dba as Southern Vermont Wellness<\/a><\/li>\n<li> <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"external_link\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/www.grassrootsvermont.com\/\">FWR, Inc. dba Grassroots Vermont<\/a><\/li>\n<li> <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"external_link\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/www.phytocarevt.com\/\">Phytoscience Institute, LLC dba PhytoCare Vermont<\/a><\/li>\n<li> <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"external_link\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/www.vtpai.org\/\">Vermont Patients Alliance, Inc.<\/a><\/li><\/ul>\n<p>The state has said it plans on opening the application process to a sixth dispensary once patient count reaches 7000 (which could happen in 2020).<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-DPSMRRegDisp_61-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-DPSMRRegDisp-61\">&#91;61&#93;<\/a><\/sup> Application fees were $2,500 and license fees set at $20,000. Annual renewal fee is $30,000.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-ChildsMedical17_62-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ChildsMedical17-62\">&#91;62&#93;<\/a><\/sup>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<b>Washington<\/b>:\n<\/p><p>The state has more than 1,050 active production licenses issued. To view the entire list, <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"external_link\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/data.lcb.wa.gov\/Licensing\/Licensed-Businesses\/u3zh-ri66\/data\">go here<\/a>, export the list, and sort out the production facilities. The state is not accepting new applications at this time. Application fees were $250, with an annual $1,480 annual license fee for producers.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-LCBProducer_63-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-LCBProducer-63\">&#91;63&#93;<\/a><\/sup>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<b>West Virginia<\/b>:\n<\/p>\n<ul><li> The state is still working on developing its medical cannabis program due to unanticipated delays<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-BPHOffice_64-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-BPHOffice-64\">&#91;64&#93;<\/a><\/sup>, particularly with finding banking solutions for the program.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-FiduraWestVirginia19_65-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-FiduraWestVirginia19-65\">&#91;65&#93;<\/a><\/sup> The Bureau for Public Health indicates that it plans on issuing no more than 10 permits for cultivators. The initial application fee will be $5,000 and the permit fee $50,000.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-BPHWest17_66-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-BPHWest17-66\">&#91;66&#93;<\/a><\/sup> The application period should open sometime in 2019.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-FiduraWestVirginia19_65-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-FiduraWestVirginia19-65\">&#91;65&#93;<\/a><\/sup> The state ceased accepting application for cultivators on February 18, 2020.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-BPHOffice_64-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-BPHOffice-64\">&#91;64&#93;<\/a><\/sup><\/li><\/ul>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Testing_labs_and_pricing_info\">Testing labs and pricing info<\/span><\/h3>\n<h4><span href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=File:Flag_of_the_United_States.png\" class=\"image wiki-link\" data-key=\"6437e0713fcd643cd81ca3437e0765c9\"><img alt=\"Flag of the United States.png\" src=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/images\/thumb\/d\/de\/Flag_of_the_United_States.png\/250px-Flag_of_the_United_States.png\" width=\"250\" height=\"132\" \/><\/a><\/div>The prevalence of testing laboratories in any given state depends on a few factors: legalization status, state laws regarding testing, and strictness of regulations. Labs typically appear as stand-alone, third-party entities. Though not common, some testing laboratories are located within dispensaries (e.g., Champlain Valley Dispensary in Vermont<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-CVDOurQuality_68-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-CVDOurQuality-68\">&#91;68&#93;<\/a><\/sup>) and treatment centers (e.g., Sanctuary ATC in New Hampshire.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-SATCAnalysis_69-0\" class=\"reference\"><a developing its medical cannabis program. Draft legislation says the Bureau for Public Health will be responsible for approving testing laboratories.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-BPHTitle64_17_87-0\" class=\"reference\"><a 2020.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-BPHOffice_64-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-BPHOffice-64\">&#91;64&#93;<\/a><\/sup>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<b>Wisconsin<\/b>:\n<\/p>\n<ul><li> <a legalized in Mexico in 2019.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-HasseThisFormer19_88-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-HasseThisFormer19-88\">&#91;88&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup it may get pushed back further.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-WilliamsNews19_90-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-WilliamsNews19-90\">&#91;90&#93;<\/a><\/sup> Even then, legalization maybe be Douglas\n<\/p><p><b>License for content<\/b>: <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"external_link\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-sa\/4.0\/\">Creative Commons Attribution-ShareAlike 4.0 International<\/a>\n<\/p><p><b>Publication date<\/b>: March 2020\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p>\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nCached time: 20200310210914\nCache expiry: 86400\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 2.006 seconds\nReal time usage: 2.442 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 87777\/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 31436\/1000000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 816508\/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 262068\/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 18\/40\nExpensive parser function count: 0\/100\n-->\n\n<!-- \nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n100.00% 1844.780 1 -
