href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Mercury_(element)\" title=\"Mercury (element)\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"dac3fd4ac66b7fb61307c056c1ccaabd\">mercury<\/a> (Hg), and <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Nickel\" title=\"Nickel\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"ed065345a0c45e5dadbb27aace1bbcd5\">nickel<\/a> (Ni).<\/li><\/ul>\n<p><br \/>\n<b><a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Mycotoxin\" title=\"Mycotoxin\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"76ccc03527f2fc7110d62c4702d9d8bc\">Mycotoxins<\/a> and microorganisms<\/b>: \"The ideal conditions for cannabis growth are also ideal for the growth of potentially harmful bacteria and fungi, including yeast and molds,\" say Shimadzu's Scott Kuzdzal and William Lipps, \"therefore microbial contamination poses health risks to consumers and immunocompromised individuals.\"<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-KuzdzalUnrav15_20-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-KuzdzalUnrav15-20\">&#91;20&#93;<\/a><\/sup> In truth, these concerns have already borne out. In fact, the University of California, Davis reported in February 2017 one of its patients had contracted an incurable fungal infection from inhaling aerosolized marijuana. They later tested 20 marijuana samples from Northern California dispensaries\u2014using specialized techniques\u2014and found a wide variety of potentially hazardous <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Microorganism\" title=\"Microorganism\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"1a8a1e22218cbeacf9ab84615f8254fe\">microorganisms<\/a>.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-UCDavis17_39-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-UCDavis17-39\">&#91;39&#93;<\/a><\/sup>\n<\/p><p>The degree to which such contaminates commonly appear in grown and stored cannabis material and to which microbiological contaminates should be tested is not clear, however. As mentioned previously, neither the U.S. EPA or neighboring Health Canada provide any significant guidance on cannabis testing, including microbiological contaminates.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-KennardYouAre16_40-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-KennardYouAre16-40\">&#91;40&#93;<\/a><\/sup> Like heavy metal testing, parallels are drawn from microbial testing guidelines and standards relating to tobacco and food, where they exist.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-KennardYouAre16_40-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-KennardYouAre16-40\">&#91;40&#93;<\/a><\/sup> As warm, moist environments are conducive to microorganism growth, maintaining stable moisture levels during cultivation and storage is essential. Regularly measuring <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Water_activity\" title=\"Water activity\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"8c9ee6a4dcc3657907ffc4c5fd81997a\">water activity<\/a>\u2014how moist something is\u2014is particularly useful as a front-line preventative tool to better ensure microbial growth is limited.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-FarrerTech15_33-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-FarrerTech15-33\">&#91;33&#93;<\/a><\/sup> Regardless, testing of some kind is still required by many U.S. states, including for organisms such as<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-KuzdzalUnrav15_20-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-KuzdzalUnrav15-20\">&#91;20&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-APHLGuide16_21-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-APHLGuide16-21\">&#91;21&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-CassidayTheHighs16_7-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-CassidayTheHighs16-7\">&#91;7&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-FarrerTech15_33-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-FarrerTech15-33\">&#91;33&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-UCDavis17_39-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-UCDavis17-39\">&#91;39&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-KennardYouAre16_40-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-KennardYouAre16-40\">&#91;40&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-CANNAMicro14_41-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-CANNAMicro14-41\">&#91;41&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-RussoCann13_42-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-RussoCann13-42\">&#91;42&#93;<\/a><\/sup>:\n<\/p>\n<ul><li> <i><a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Alternaria\" title=\"Alternaria\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"cfee8382e40f63143cf99a8975053dea\">Alternaria<\/a><\/i><\/li>\n<li> <i><a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Aspergillus\" title=\"Aspergillus\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"424ebb812aa96d73372105893eb3d2ac\">Aspergillus<\/a><\/i><\/li>\n<li> <i>Cryptococcus<\/i><\/li>\n<li> <i><a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Escherichia_coli\" title=\"Escherichia coli\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"5a3241c3e6749e1014285a38134e9f6c\">E. coli<\/a><\/i><\/li>\n<li> <i>Mucor<\/i><\/li>\n<li> <i><a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Penicillium\" title=\"Penicillium\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"569f7764647b1477fde1a52f7ef2530b\">Penicillium<\/a><\/i><\/li>\n<li> <i><a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Salmonella\" title=\"Salmonella\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"f161d59d89a98c21ad00ad8e39f20e4f\">Salmonella<\/a><\/i><\/li><\/ul>\n<p><br \/>\n<\/p>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Methods_and_guidelines\">Methods and guidelines<\/span><\/h3>\n<p>Now that we've addressed what's being tested for, we can move on to how they're being tested and what's being done to improve testing methods and procedures, including associated guidelines and recommendations. It would be beyond the scope of this guide to include every state's laws and guidelines on cannabis testing; entities such as <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"external_link\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/www.leafly.com\/news\/industry\/leaflys-state-by-state-guide-to-cannabis-testing-regulations\">Leafly Holdings<\/a><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-RoughLeaflysState_43-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-RoughLeaflysState-43\">&#91;43&#93;<\/a><\/sup> and <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"external_link\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http:\/\/norml.org\/states\">NORML<\/a><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-NORMLStates_44-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-NORMLStates-44\">&#91;44&#93;<\/a><\/sup> provide such online resources. Instead, this section will focus on current and promising techniques using generalizations based on information from multiple sources. If any guidelines and recommendations are known, they'll be included.\n<\/p>\n<h4><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Sampling\">Sampling<\/span><\/h4>\n<p>Random, representative sampling is encouraged. When dealing with solid cannabis, BOTEC Analysis recommends a \"quartering\" method that divides the sample into four equal parts and takes portions from opposite sections of a square-shaped arrangement of the sample. For liquid cannabis products, remembering to stir before sample collection is advised.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-APHLGuide16_21-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-APHLGuide16-21\">&#91;21&#93;<\/a><\/sup> When deriving a sample from a cannabis-laden edible, the <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Quechers\" title=\"Quechers\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"af67a9ed87921d0a448df9cada475eb4\">QuEChERS<\/a> approach used by food safety labs for pesticide testing has practical use.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-RigdonExtract16_45-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-RigdonExtract16-45\">&#91;45&#93;<\/a><\/sup> In fact, a variety of parallels have been drawn from the food and herbal medicine industries' sampling guidelines, including from the Codex Alimentarius Commission's <i>CAC\/GL 50-2004 General Guidelines on Sampling<\/i> as well as various chapters of the <i><a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=United_States_Pharmacopeia\" title=\"United States Pharmacopeia\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"d467dceefa8c014c6fd31441d2fb6632\">United States Pharmacopeia and The National Formulary<\/a><\/i>.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-APHLGuide16_21-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-APHLGuide16-21\">&#91;21&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-CACGL50-2004_46-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-CACGL50-2004-46\">&#91;46&#93;<\/a><\/sup> As the Association of Public Health Laboratories (APHL) points out, \"[g]ood sampling is key to improving analytical data equivalency among organizations,\" and it provides a solid base for any future testing and standardization efforts.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-APHLGuide16_21-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-APHLGuide16-21\">&#91;21&#93;<\/a><\/sup> \n<\/p><p>Additional sampling insight can be found by examining other states' guidelines, e.g., Massachusetts' <i>Protocol for Sampling and Analysis of Finished Medical Marijuana Products and Marijuana-Infused Products for Massachusetts Registered Medical Marijuana Dispensaries<\/i>.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-DPHMassProto16_47-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-DPHMassProto16-47\">&#91;47&#93;<\/a><\/sup>\n<\/p>\n<h4><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Cannabinoid_testing\">Cannabinoid testing<\/span><\/h4>\n<p>Quantifying cannabinoids for label accuracy is a major goal of testing, though calculation and testing processes may vary slightly from state to state. Despite any differences, laboratorians generally agree that when testing for cannabinoids such as THC and CBD, as well as their respective biosynthetic precursors THCA and CBDA, the methodology used must be scrutinized. The naturally occurring THCA of cannabis isn't psychoactive; it requires <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Decarboxylation\" title=\"Decarboxylation\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"d193a62772bddc5385f7d9c5e8543446\">decarboxylation<\/a> (a chemical reaction induced by drying\/heating that releases carbon dioxide) to convert itself into the psychoactive cannabinoid THC. Chemical calculations show that the process of decarboxylation results in approximately 87.7 percent of the THCA's mass converting to THC, with the other 12.3 percent bubbling off as CO<sub>2<\/sub> gas.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-CAWhy1_48-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-CAWhy1-48\">&#91;48&#93;<\/a><\/sup> The problem with this in the testing domain is <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Gas_chromatography\" title=\"Gas chromatography\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"5094f035cb8bead5003deb9181e398b8\">gas chromatography<\/a> (GC) involves heating the sample solution. If you, the lab technician, require precise numbers of both THCA and THC, then GC analysis poses the risk of under-reporting THC total values.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-APHLGuide16_21-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-APHLGuide16-21\">&#91;21&#93;<\/a><\/sup> As such, <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Chromatography#Liquid_chromatography\" title=\"Chromatography\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"da43e6566dd6693473e320ebadde934f\">liquid chromatography<\/a>-<a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Chromatography_detector\" title=\"Chromatography detector\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"7787a159a1c7c0a3b2cc28bbc3189587\">diode array detection<\/a> (LC-DAD) may be required if a concise profile of all cannabinoids must be made, primarily because it provides environmental stability for them all during analysis. If GC is used, the analysis requires extra considerations such as sample derivatization.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-APHLGuide16_21-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-APHLGuide16-21\">&#91;21&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-CassidayTheHighs16_7-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-CassidayTheHighs16-7\">&#91;7&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-RigdonAccurateJuly15_49-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-RigdonAccurateJuly15-49\">&#91;49&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-RigdonAccurateSept15_50-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-RigdonAccurateSept15-50\">&#91;50&#93;<\/a><\/sup>\n<\/p><p>The APHL briefly describes analysis methods of cannabinoids using both LC and GC on pages 31\u201332 of their May 2016 <i>Guidance for State Medical Cannabis Testing Programs<\/i>. They also point to New York Department of Health - Wadsworth Center's various guidance documents (MML-300, -301, and -303) for methodologies when testing sample types other than solids, particularly using <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=High-performance_liquid_chromatography\" title=\"High-performance liquid chromatography\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"4c5d83ffa9785383c3eb0be7ea78dd2b\">high-performance liquid chromatography<\/a> photodiode array detection (HPLC-PAD).<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-APHLGuide16_21-10\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-APHLGuide16-21\">&#91;21&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-MML-300_51-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-MML-300-51\">&#91;51&#93;<\/a><\/sup> Also worth noting is that <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=ASTM_International\" title=\"ASTM International\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"4211bf55f9dcffbe89190f350eaaf00c\">ASTM<\/a>'s Subcommittee D37.03 is working on various standard methods for determining cannabinoid concentrations using different chromatography techniques<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-ASTMSubD37.03_52-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ASTMSubD37.03-52\">&#91;52&#93;<\/a><\/sup>, while the Association of Official Agricultural Chemists (AOAC) has already developed a Standard Method Performance Requirement (SMPR) for analyzing cannabinoids in <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Hemp\" title=\"Hemp\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"c23e30b6cf1df54f1dc338492c9f9da2\">hemp<\/a> (i.e., low THC cannabis varieties).<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-AOACNew19_53-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-AOACNew19-53\">&#91;53&#93;<\/a><\/sup> Overall, methods used in cannabinoid testing include<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-APHLGuide16_21-11\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-APHLGuide16-21\">&#91;21&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-CassidayTheHighs16_7-10\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-CassidayTheHighs16-7\">&#91;7&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-MML-300_51-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-MML-300-51\">&#91;51&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-LeghissaDetection18_54-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-LeghissaDetection18-54\">&#91;54&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-SCCann16_55-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-SCCann16-55\">&#91;55&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-AdamsNear16_56-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-AdamsNear16-56\">&#91;56&#93;<\/a><\/sup>:\n<\/p>\n<ul><li> <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Fourier-transform_infrared_spectroscopy\" title=\"Fourier-transform infrared spectroscopy\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"ed4db292d8cae0aec6becf614dfa9bff\">Fourier-transform infrared spectroscopy<\/a> (FTIR; has limitations, such as requiring standard samples tested w\/ other methods)<\/li>\n<li> Gas chromatography-flame ionization detection (GC-FID; requires sample derivatization for both acid and neutral compounds; good with standards like 5\u03b1-cholestane, docosane, and tetracosane)<\/li>\n<li> <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Gas_chromatography%E2%80%93mass_spectrometry\" title=\"Gas chromatography\u2013mass spectrometry\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"afbcab5867e499fab32b49e2b77c9e32\">Gas chromatography\u2013mass spectrometry<\/a> (GC-MS; requires sample derivatization for both acid and neutral compounds; good with standards like deuterated cannabinoids)<\/li>\n<li> <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Gas_chromatography%E2%80%93vacuum_ultraviolet_spectroscopy\" title=\"Gas chromatography\u2013vacuum ultraviolet spectroscopy\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"1395b0ea031074c5225c2770a71f85a1\">Gas chromatography\u2013vacuum ultraviolet spectroscopy<\/a> (GC-VUV)<\/li>\n<li> High-performance liquid chromatography photodiode array detection (HPLC-PAD; stable for all forms of cannabinoids)<\/li>\n<li> High-performance liquid chromatography UV detection (HPLC-UV)<\/li>\n<li> <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Supercritical_fluid_chromatography\" title=\"Supercritical fluid chromatography\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"e8a4c554e3c2e7591c15ffcf06b35314\">Supercritical fluid chromatography<\/a> (SFC; newer technology w\/ added benefits)<\/li>\n<li> <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Thin-layer_chromatography\" title=\"Thin-layer chromatography\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"c8f68c661f30ba974342dd75a4081655\">Thin-layer chromatography<\/a> (TLC; older, less common technology)<\/li>\n<li> <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=High-performance_liquid_chromatography#Pump_pressure\" title=\"High-performance liquid chromatography\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"6badcd680b93b3cc1987ac107006f7d7\">Ultra-performance chromatography<\/a> (UPC; newer technology w\/ added benefits)<\/li><\/ul>\n<p>Also worthy of note is recent investigation of viably using <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Nuclear_magnetic_resonance_spectroscopy\" title=\"Nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"b571fe2c0aeb1614f1b19dbe1b12f7f3\">nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) spectroscopy<\/a> as a more affordable and rapid solution to identifying cannabinoid contents and profiles of samples. Conferences<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-ZilerRecap19_57-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ZilerRecap19-57\">&#91;57&#93;<\/a><\/sup>, research<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-WangComp17_58-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-WangComp17-58\">&#91;58&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-MarchettiUseOf19_59-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-MarchettiUseOf19-59\">&#91;59&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-SiudemRapid19_60-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-SiudemRapid19-60\">&#91;60&#93;<\/a><\/sup>, and articles<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-MayNMR17_61-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-MayNMR17-61\">&#91;61&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-BennettCanna18_62-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-BennettCanna18-62\">&#91;62&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-ConnCanna19_63-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ConnCanna19-63\">&#91;63&#93;<\/a><\/sup> over the last few years have advanced the use of NMR spectroscopy for cannabinoid analysis.\n<\/p>\n<h4><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Terpene_testing\">Terpene testing<\/span><\/h4>\n<p>Identifying and quantifying terpenes is one of the more difficult tasks facing laboratorians<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-CassidayTheHighs16_7-11\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-CassidayTheHighs16-7\">&#91;7&#93;<\/a><\/sup>:\n<\/p>\n<blockquote>Terpenes present an analytical challenge because they are <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Chemical_polarity#Nonpolar_molecules\" title=\"Chemical polarity\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"f4827cf163954f0fb5f445407d00e3aa\">nonpolar<\/a> and structurally similar, and many structural <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Isomer\" title=\"Isomer\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"9546fdf366e11cd699a1d8a087bb41e3\">isomers<\/a> exist. <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Mass_spectrometry\" title=\"Mass spectrometry\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"18314b70982e52d5a81db4a757d6461f\">Mass spectrometry<\/a> (MS) cannot distinguish terpenes that co-elute from a GC column because many have the same molecular weight and share fragment ions.<\/blockquote>\n<p>Of course, types of gas chromatography work; but like cannabinoids, terpenes can degrade with the high heat of gas chromatography.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-AdamsNear16_56-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-AdamsNear16-56\">&#91;56&#93;<\/a><\/sup> Combined with the problems mentioned above, highly specialized gas chromatography processes that include additional steps, such as full evaporation technique headspace gas chromatography flame ionization detection (FET-HS-GC-FID), can be used to produce cleaner results, particularly for volatile components.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-CassidayTheHighs16_7-12\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-CassidayTheHighs16-7\">&#91;7&#93;<\/a><\/sup> It's less clear if high-performance liquid chromatography (HPLC) is used frequently; some entities such as Eurofins Experchem Laboratories claim HPLC works best for them<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-AdamsNear16_56-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-AdamsNear16-56\">&#91;56&#93;<\/a><\/sup>, while others such as Restek Corporation claim the method is problematic at best.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-HerringCanHP16_64-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-HerringCanHP16-64\">&#91;64&#93;<\/a><\/sup>\n<\/p><p>Overall, methods for terpene identification and analysis include<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-CassidayTheHighs16_7-13\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-CassidayTheHighs16-7\">&#91;7&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-SCLabs_29-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-SCLabs-29\">&#91;29&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-SCCann16_55-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-SCCann16-55\">&#91;55&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-HodgsonVacuum18_65-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-HodgsonVacuum18-65\">&#91;65&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-AdamsNear16_56-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-AdamsNear16-56\">&#91;56&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-ShimadzuCLTS_66-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ShimadzuCLTS-66\">&#91;66&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-CEMAnal18_67-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-CEMAnal18-67\">&#91;67&#93;<\/a><\/sup>:\n<\/p>\n<ul><li> Full evaporation technique\u2013headspace\u2013gas chromatography\u2013flame ionization detection (FET-HS-GC-FID; tends to be semi-quantitative)<\/li>\n<li> Gas chromatography\u2013flame ionization detection (GC-FID)<\/li>\n<li> Gas chromatography\u2013mass spectrometry (GC-MS)<\/li>\n<li> Gas chromatography\u2013vacuum ultraviolet spectroscopy (GC-VUV)<\/li>\n<li> <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Headspace_gas_chromatography_for_dissolved_gas_measurement\" title=\"Headspace gas chromatography for dissolved gas measurement\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"8583e881cbb0fbdb5cf0aa1f1ffed702\">Headspace\u2013gas chromatography<\/a>\u2013mass spectrometry (HS-GC-MS)<\/li>\n<li> Headspace\u2013solid-phase microextraction (HS-SPME)<\/li>\n<li> High-performance liquid chromatography (HPLC; may have limitations due to coelution of terpenes and cannabinoids at certain ranges<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-HerringCanHP16_64-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-HerringCanHP16-64\">&#91;64&#93;<\/a><\/sup>)<\/li><\/ul>\n<h4><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Contaminate_testing\">Contaminate testing<\/span><\/h4>\n<div class=\"floatright\"><a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=File:LC_MS_pic.jpg\" class=\"image wiki-link\" data-key=\"ed7db9379ddf8b18a138f8c49ead409b\"><img alt=\"LC MS pic.jpg\" src=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/images\/thumb\/0\/02\/LC_MS_pic.jpg\/400px-LC_MS_pic.jpg\" style=\"width: 100%;max-width: 400px;height: auto;\" \/><\/a><\/div><b>Pesticides<\/b>: Gas and liquid chromatography methods are by and large the staple of testing methods for pesticides, which remain \"the hardest analyses that are going to be done in the cannabis industry.\"<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-CassidayTheHighs16_7-14\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-CassidayTheHighs16-7\">&#91;7&#93;<\/a><\/sup> Notably, high-performance liquid chromatography\u2013tandem-mass spectrometry (HPLC-MS\/MS) tends to be one of the most thorough methods says Emerald Scientific's CTO Amanda Rigdon. \"Ninety-five percent of the pesticides out there can be analyzed by HPLC-MS\/MS, although there are some that you would need a GC-MS\/MS for,\" she says.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-CassidayTheHighs16_7-15\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-CassidayTheHighs16-7\">&#91;7&#93;<\/a><\/sup> A popular sample extraction method for detecting multiple pesticide residues in cannabis is the QuEChERS (quick, easy, cheap, effective, rugged, and safe) method, which shows \"acceptable recoveries and relative standard deviations\" for almost all known pesticides<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-DePalmaChallenges18_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-DePalmaChallenges18-1\">&#91;1&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-LCGCTrends16_68-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-LCGCTrends16-68\">&#91;68&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-KowalskiEval17_69-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-KowalskiEval17-69\">&#91;69&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-WinklerPesticide18_70-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-WinklerPesticide18-70\">&#91;70&#93;<\/a><\/sup>, though the release of heat and increase in pH of QuECHERS may degrade particularly sensitive pesticides in the sample.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-JordanAComp18_71-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-JordanAComp18-71\">&#91;71&#93;<\/a><\/sup> However, other methods such as solvent extraction (such as with acetonitrile) with dispersive solid-phase extraction (dSPE) cleanup<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-LCGCTrends16_68-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-LCGCTrends16-68\">&#91;68&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-WinklerPesticide18_70-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-WinklerPesticide18-70\">&#91;70&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-JordanAComp18_71-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-JordanAComp18-71\">&#91;71&#93;<\/a><\/sup> and energized dispersive guided extraction (EDGE) may also been used.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-CEMAnal18_67-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-CEMAnal18-67\">&#91;67&#93;<\/a><\/sup> Common testing methods that have been used, after sample preparation, include<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-APHLGuide16_21-12\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-APHLGuide16-21\">&#91;21&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-ShimadzuCLTS_66-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ShimadzuCLTS-66\">&#91;66&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-CEMAnal18_67-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-CEMAnal18-67\">&#91;67&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-KowalskiEval17_69-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-KowalskiEval17-69\">&#91;69&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-WinklerPesticide18_70-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-WinklerPesticide18-70\">&#91;70&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-JordanAComp18_71-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-JordanAComp18-71\">&#91;71&#93;<\/a><\/sup>:\n<ul><li> Gas chromatography\u2013electron capture detection (GC-ECD)<\/li>\n<li> Gas chromatography\u2013mass spectrometry (GC-MS)<\/li>\n<li> Gas chromatography\u2013tandem-mass spectrometry (GC-MS\/MS)<\/li>\n<li> Liquid chromatography\u2013mass spectrometry (LC-MS; also high-performance or HPLC-MS)<\/li>\n<li> Liquid chromatography\u2013tandem-mass spectrometry (LC-MS\/MS; also high-performance or HPLC-MS\/MS)<\/li><\/ul>\n<p>For quantification of pesticides in cannabis, the AOAC's SMPR 2018.011, EPA's Residue Analytical Methods (RAM), and FDA's Pesticide Analytical Manual (PAM) provide guidance to labs.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-APHLGuide16_21-13\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-APHLGuide16-21\">&#91;21&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-SMPR2018.011_72-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-SMPR2018.011-72\">&#91;72&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-EPAResidue17_73-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-EPAResidue17-73\">&#91;73&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-FDA_PAM_74-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-FDA_PAM-74\">&#91;74&#93;<\/a><\/sup>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<b>Solvents<\/b>: Testing for solvents is largely standardized into a few options, which have parallels to existing pharmaceutical testing standards outlined in Chapter 467 of <i>United States Pharmacopeia and The National Formulary<\/i> (USP &lt;467&gt;)<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-USPNF467_36-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-USPNF467-36\">&#91;36&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-APHLGuide16_21-14\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-APHLGuide16-21\">&#91;21&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-CassidayTheHighs16_7-16\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-CassidayTheHighs16-7\">&#91;7&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-ShimadzuCLTS_66-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ShimadzuCLTS-66\">&#91;66&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-PocevaOpti16_75-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-PocevaOpti16-75\">&#91;75&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-L.27HeureuxAdvancing18_76-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-L.27HeureuxAdvancing18-76\">&#91;76&#93;<\/a><\/sup>:\n<\/p>\n<ul><li> Headspace\u2013gas chromatography\/mass spectrometry (HS-GC\/MS)<\/li>\n<li> Headspace\u2013gas chromatography\u2013flame ionization detection\u2013mass spectrometry (HS-GC-FID-MS)<\/li>\n<li> Full evaporation technique\u2013headspace\u2013gas chromatography\u2013flame ionization detection (FET-HS-GC-FID)<\/li><\/ul>\n<p>Massachusetts and Oregon\u2014and likely other states\u2014have used a variety of guidance documents such as USP &lt;467&gt;, reports from the Commission of the European Communities' Scientific Committee on Food (now the European Food Safety Authority), and the International Conference on Harmonization's (ICH) Q3C(R5)<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-APHLGuide16_21-15\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-APHLGuide16-21\">&#91;21&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-MDPHResponse_37-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-MDPHResponse-37\">&#91;37&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-FarrerTech15_33-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-FarrerTech15-33\">&#91;33&#93;<\/a><\/sup> to set their action level testing values for particular solvents. The AOAC provides another standardized option in the form of their SMPR 2019.002.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-SMPR2019.002_77-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-SMPR2019.002-77\">&#91;77&#93;<\/a><\/sup>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<b>Heavy metals<\/b>: The methods used for quantifying levels of highly toxic metals in plants depend on ease-of-use, level of accuracy, and overall cost. Sample preparation typically includes the use of closed-vessel <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Microwave_digestion\" title=\"Microwave digestion\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"2cb1505ef4d8b4cf909afc078a3d8686\">microwave digestion<\/a> to get the sample into solution for analysis.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-CEMAnal18_67-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-CEMAnal18-67\">&#91;67&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-BoyleSelecting18_78-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-BoyleSelecting18-78\">&#91;78&#93;<\/a><\/sup> Once prepared, the following methods are most common for testing cannabis and other plants for heavy metals<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-KuzdzalACloser16_6-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-KuzdzalACloser16-6\">&#91;6&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-APHLGuide16_21-16\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-APHLGuide16-21\">&#91;21&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-CassidayTheHighs16_7-17\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-CassidayTheHighs16-7\">&#91;7&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-DavisAnalysis15_79-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-DavisAnalysis15-79\">&#91;79&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-ShimadzuCLTS_66-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ShimadzuCLTS-66\">&#91;66&#93;<\/a><\/sup>:\n<\/p>\n<ul><li> <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Inductively_coupled_plasma_atomic_emission_spectroscopy\" title=\"Inductively coupled plasma atomic emission spectroscopy\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"c3d9e1c4597891de8e869097753f2c66\">Inductively coupled plasma\u2013atomic emission spectroscopy<\/a> (ICP-AES), sometimes called inductively coupled plasma optical emission spectrometry (ICP-OES) (at times coupled with an ultrasonic nebulizer)<\/li>\n<li> <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Inductively_coupled_plasma_mass_spectrometry\" title=\"Inductively coupled plasma mass spectrometry\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"c6672e2589461965c5081045a2541904\">Inductively coupled plasma\u2013mass spectrometry<\/a> (ICP-MS)<\/li>\n<li> Inductively coupled plasma\u2013tandem-mass spectroscopy (ICP-MS\/MS)<\/li><\/ul>\n<p>For quantification of metals in cannabis, the U.S. FDA's ICP-MS methodology document is often used.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-APHLGuide16_21-17\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-APHLGuide16-21\">&#91;21&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-FDAAnalysisofFoods11_80-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-FDAAnalysisofFoods11-80\">&#91;80&#93;<\/a><\/sup>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<b>Mycotoxins and microorganisms<\/b>: A standard method of testing for the existence of microorganisms is through the process of culturing a sample in a Petri dish, a common diagnostic method in microbiology. <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=ELISA\" title=\"ELISA\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"1faf36073c6f205521c4be4ea8f7ed55\">Enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay<\/a> (ELISA) is also used, particularly to identify mycotoxins. However, Petri culture analysis isn't rigorous, and ELISA can be time consuming, as it's limited to one mycotoxin per test.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-KuzdzalACloser16_6-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-KuzdzalACloser16-6\">&#91;6&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-CassidayTheHighs16_7-18\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-CassidayTheHighs16-7\">&#91;7&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-KennardYouAre16_40-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-KennardYouAre16-40\">&#91;40&#93;<\/a><\/sup> The following are other, more precise techniques that are improving laboratorians' analyses, particularly using DNA snippets of microbiological contaminates<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-KuzdzalACloser16_6-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-KuzdzalACloser16-6\">&#91;6&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-CassidayTheHighs16_7-19\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-CassidayTheHighs16-7\">&#91;7&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-KennardYouAre16_40-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-KennardYouAre16-40\">&#91;40&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-ThompsonAMicro16_81-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ThompsonAMicro16-81\">&#91;81&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-L.27HeureuxTesting18_82-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-L.27HeureuxTesting18-82\">&#91;82&#93;<\/a><\/sup>:\n<\/p>\n<ul><li> <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Real-time_polymerase_chain_reaction\" title=\"Real-time polymerase chain reaction\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"f7a72b7ed6d334f020eda48dd541f85c\">Quantitative polymerase chain reaction<\/a> (qPCR)<\/li>\n<li> <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Shotgun_sequencing#Metagenomic_shotgun_sequencing\" title=\"Shotgun sequencing\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"8027a4493b1a3cf18272b85f20121b34\">Whole metagenome shotgun (WMGS) sequencing<\/a><\/li>\n<li> <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Matrix-assisted_laser_desorption\/ionization\" title=\"Matrix-assisted laser desorption\/ionization\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"f4a84192f5de5587156a0b061bcdace5\">Matrix-assisted laser desorption\/ionization<\/a> (MALDI)<\/li>\n<li> High-performance liquid chromatography (HPLC)<\/li>\n<li> Liquid chromatography\u2013tandem-mass spectrometry (LC-MS\/MS)<\/li>\n<li> Liquid chromatography\u2013electrospray ionization\u2013tandem-mass spectrometry (LC-ESI-MS\/MS)<\/li>\n<li> Liquid chromatography\u2013atmospheric pressure chemical ionization\u2013tandem-mass spectrometry (LC-APCI-MS\/MS)<\/li><\/ul>\n<p>The extent of mycotoxin testing required remains in question by several entities. The APHL claims \"[t]here is no readily available evidence to support the contention that cannabis harbors significant levels of mycotoxins.\"<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-APHLGuide16_21-18\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-APHLGuide16-21\">&#91;21&#93;<\/a><\/sup> The Oregon Health Authority takes a more middle-ground approach, noting that testing for <i>E. coli<\/i> and <i>Salmonella<\/i> will \"protect public health,\" though <i>Aspergillus<\/i> only deserves a warning for people with suppressed immune systems due to its prevalence in the environment.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-FarrerTech15_33-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-FarrerTech15-33\">&#91;33&#93;<\/a><\/sup> USP &lt;561&gt; recommendations largely limit mycotoxin testing of botanical products to those borne from root or <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Rhizome\" title=\"Rhizome\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"8020777578dd3a032e45e5ced78d983c\">rhizome<\/a> material<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-USPNF561_83-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-USPNF561-83\">&#91;83&#93;<\/a><\/sup>, \"which THC-containing cannabis products presumably do not possess,\" emphasizes the APHL.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-APHLGuide16_21-19\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-APHLGuide16-21\">&#91;21&#93;<\/a><\/sup> Regardless, U.S. Pharmacopeia's Chapter 561 remains a useful document for testing guidelines and limits regarding microbials<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-USPNF561_83-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-USPNF561-83\">&#91;83&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-APHLGuide16_21-20\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-APHLGuide16-21\">&#91;21&#93;<\/a><\/sup>, as does the AOAC's SMPR 2019.001 for the detection of <i>Aspergillus<\/i>.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-SMPR2019.001_84-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-SMPR2019.001-84\">&#91;84&#93;<\/a><\/sup> In the less common case of dealing with powdered cannabis\u2014a relatively new THC extract form\u2014Chapter 2023 provides at least some testing parallels, though Dr. Tony Cundell, a microbiologist consulting for the pharmaceutical industry, suggests USP &lt;2023&gt; doesn't go far enough for immunocompromised patients.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-CundellMicro15_85-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-CundellMicro15-85\">&#91;85&#93;<\/a><\/sup>\n<\/p><p>Somewhat related and worth mentioning is moisture content testing. As previously mentioned, warm, moist environments are conducive to microorganism growth, and regularly measuring water activity is useful for the prevention of microbial growth.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-FarrerTech15_33-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-FarrerTech15-33\">&#91;33&#93;<\/a><\/sup> The APHL references specifications from the Dutch Office of Medical Cannabis that recommend water content be between five to ten percent in cannabis.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-APHLGuide16_21-21\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-APHLGuide16-21\">&#91;21&#93;<\/a><\/sup>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Laboratory_accreditation\">Laboratory accreditation<\/span><\/h3>\n<p>The accreditation of a cannabis testing laboratory should also be briefly addressed. As it currently stands, these labs and their relevant tests are typically accredited to the <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=ISO\/IEC_17025\" title=\"ISO\/IEC 17025\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"fb6aed7114b8c5fdf16c569526d6ce48\">ISO\/IEC 17025<\/a> standard. This includes the likes of the ANSI National Accreditation Board (ANAB)<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-ANABCanna_86-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ANABCanna-86\">&#91;86&#93;<\/a><\/sup> and the American Association of Laboratory Accreditation (A2LA).<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-A2LACanna_87-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-A2LACanna-87\">&#91;87&#93;<\/a><\/sup> However, through the American Council of Independent Laboratories (ACIL) and its Cannabis Working Group (CWG), a specific national standard for cannabis lab accreditation is beginning to take shape. Referred to as CanNaLap (Cannabis National Laboratory Accreditation Program) and based on ISO\/IEC 17025, the national standard has been developed \"as a mechanism to ensure the effective performance of all cannabis testing labs operating in the United States.\"<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-ACILCanna19_88-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ACILCanna19-88\">&#91;88&#93;<\/a><\/sup> Additionally, the ACIL also seeks for the FDA and U.S. Department of Agriculture (USDA) to \"support and endorse\" CanNaLap \"as a means to establish standards of competency for testing market participants.\"<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-ACILCanna19_88-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ACILCanna19-88\">&#91;88&#93;<\/a><\/sup> ANAB has already begun to address CanNaLap as part of its supplemental accreditation requirements<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-ANABCanna_86-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ANABCanna-86\">&#91;86&#93;<\/a><\/sup>, though time will tell if CanNaLap becomes a fully adopted nation accreditation standard in the U.S.\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Reports\">Reports<\/span><\/h3>\n<p>There's little in the way of standardization for lab reporting of cannabis test results, though some U.S. states have outlined requirements for what must be included in such reports. The Oregon Health Authority's <i>Oregon Administrative Rules, Chapter 333, Division 64, Section 0100: Marijuana Item Sampling Procedures and Testing<\/i> stipulates that any report must include total THC and total CBD (by dry weight) and, if discovered, \"up to five tentatively identified compounds (TICS) that have the greatest apparent concentration.\" It also lays out requirements for pesticides, failed tests, limits of quantification, and specimen identifiers such as test batch number.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-OHA333-064-0100_89-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-OHA333-064-0100-89\">&#91;89&#93;<\/a><\/sup> \n<\/p><p>In late January 2017, Pennsylvania released its temporary regulations in support of its new medical marijuana program (28 Pa. Code Chapter 1171), which includes a section on test results and reporting (1171.31). The regulations stipulate reporting by electronic tracking system, with stipulations on using certificates of analysis which include lot\/batch number and the specific compounds and contaminates tested.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-28PA1171_90-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-28PA1171-90\">&#91;90&#93;<\/a><\/sup> Regulations aside, it's largely up to the laboratory\u2014and often by extension, the software they're using\u2014to decide how a report is formatted. Some labs like Seattle-based Analytical 360 offer clean, color-based certificates of analysis, with high-magnification photographs, the chromatogram, potency, cannabinoid content, contaminate content, and explanation of limits, with the name of the approving analyst.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-CC_A360_91-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-CC_A360-91\">&#91;91&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-C360Results_92-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-C360Results-92\">&#91;92&#93;<\/a><\/sup> Others may simply generate a computer printout with the basic data and a legend.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-HydrioCan16_93-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-HydrioCan16-93\">&#91;93&#93;<\/a><\/sup> Reports may originate from the measuring device itself (e.g., an integrator in a chromatography device), a middleware or data station attached to the instrument, or a laboratory information management system (LIMS) that accepted data from the instrument.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-McKennaSetting15_94-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-McKennaSetting15-94\">&#91;94&#93;<\/a><\/sup>\n<\/p><p>Though not directly related to laboratory testing, it's worth noting states also have their own reporting requirements for growers, processors, and dispensaries. Both Oregon and Washington, for example, require monthly reports related to medical marijuana transfers.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-OMMPReporting_95-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-OMMPReporting-95\">&#91;95&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-314-55_WAC_96-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-314-55_WAC-96\">&#91;96&#93;<\/a><\/sup>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Lab_equipment\">Lab equipment<\/span><\/h3>\n<p>As indicated in previous sections, spectrometry and chromatography have played and will continue to play an important role in cannabis laboratory testing. This should not be surprising: \"mass spectrometry is superior to other spectral techniques in such features as sensitivity, selectivity, generation possibility of molecular mass\/formula, and combinability with chromatography.\"<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-MilmanTech10_97-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-MilmanTech10-97\">&#91;97&#93;<\/a><\/sup> Analyzing complex chemical compounds that have many features and which are at times difficult to differentiate from each other proves challenging, but these technologies excel in meeting that task.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-MilmanTech10_97-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-MilmanTech10-97\">&#91;97&#93;<\/a><\/sup> Refer to the previous \"Methods and guidelines\" section to note the specific technology associated with each molecule and contaminate. Aside from spectrometry and chromatography equipment, the analysis of microorganisms in cannabis may turn to DNA analysis methods that require additional equipment such as a thermal cycler (qPCR) or sequencer (WMGS), or ELISA, which utilizes a photometer or spectrophotometer. Of course, preparing and storing samples requires equipment as well, such as microplates, centrifuges, comparison standards, capillaries, chemicals, columns, Petri dishes, scales, and disposable gloves. Software-based data management systems may also constitute equipment and are discussed in the next section.\n<\/p><p>When it comes to purchasing lab equipment specifically for cannabis testing, a 2015 interview with Emerald Scientific's CTO Amanda Rigdon (then with Restek Corporation) provides good advice<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-TaylorCanna15_98-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-TaylorCanna15-98\">&#91;98&#93;<\/a><\/sup>:\n<\/p>\n<ul><li> Industry-specific instrumentation isn't needed in most cases as most of the techniques and equipment used in food and herbal medicine testing have strong parallels to cannabis testing.<\/li>\n<li> That said, some sample preparation tools, standards, and consumables specifically marketed to the industry may very well make the job quicker and more reliable.<\/li>\n<li> Appropriate sample preparation techniques are just as vital as the equipment you use.<\/li>\n<li> Do your research; many instrument companies are examining methodologies usable on conventional equipment, lessening the need for more expensive devices.<\/li>\n<li> If buying used equipment, make sure the original manufacturer is still in business and producing consumables and replacement parts. Make sure your planned methods match the equipment, and make sure it's not so old that it can't be serviced by a qualified technician.<\/li><\/ul>\n<p>For more on specific laboratory equipment and vendors, see the fifth chapter in this guide.\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Software\">Software<\/span><\/h3>\n<p>Laboratories increasingly depend on software to analyze, store, and share critical data from instruments and experiments.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-VI11_99-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-VI11-99\">&#91;99&#93;<\/a><\/sup> This has led to the development of laboratory-specific software like the <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Laboratory_information_management_system\" title=\"Laboratory information management system\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"300b107ea507dc9077934f573fc2f6d6\">laboratory information management system<\/a> (LIMS), <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Electronic_laboratory_notebook\" title=\"Electronic laboratory notebook\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"330980cdcbe270b3820732ed0cccc7d4\">electronic laboratory notebook<\/a> (ELN), and <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Chromatography_data_system\" title=\"Chromatography data system\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"2bcff0188095fae94e3a6a8726206ba8\">chromatography data system<\/a> (CDS; sometimes CDMS). These and other software systems such as \"seed-to-sale\" programs can also play an important role in the cannabis testing laboratory.\n<\/p>\n<h4><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"LIMS\">LIMS<\/span><\/h4>\n<p>Laboratories of all types use LIMS software to manage the wide variety of data, testing and analysis <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Workflow\" title=\"Workflow\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"c63a2fc4c276562dbdaf957f640d69cb\">workflows<\/a>, and other enterprise activities typical of them. This generally includes\u2014but is not limited to\u2014sample receipt, workflow management, sample tracking and analysis, <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Laboratory_quality_control\" title=\"Laboratory quality control\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"6543ec3fb55c67d60f41473697c0781d\">quality control<\/a>, instrument data management, data storage, reporting and document management.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-SkobelevLab11_100-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-SkobelevLab11-100\">&#91;100&#93;<\/a><\/sup> The cannabis testing laboratory is no exception, though its activities differ slightly from, for example, a clinical pathology laboratory. As such, a few additional features outside of what's typically found in a generic LIMS are required.\n<\/p><p>Features that may be incorporated into a cannabis testing LIMS that you might not necessarily find in an all-purpose LIMS include<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-BirosUsing15_101-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-BirosUsing15-101\">&#91;101&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-PromiumELIMSCanna_102-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-PromiumELIMSCanna-102\">&#91;102&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-LLLIMSCanna_103-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-LLLIMSCanna-103\">&#91;103&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-AudinoManag18_104-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-AudinoManag18-104\">&#91;104&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-PaszkoSelecting18_105-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-PaszkoSelecting18-105\">&#91;105&#93;<\/a><\/sup>:\n<\/p>\n<ul><li> sample loading screens optimized for the industry, including differentiation between medical and recreational marijuana<\/li>\n<li> pre-loaded compliant test protocols, labels, and reports optimized and readily adjustable for a rapidly changing industry<\/li>\n<li> tools for creating new, compliant test protocols, labels, and reports<\/li>\n<li> a web API to integrate with state-required compliance reporting systems<\/li>\n<li> chain-of-custody (CoC) tracking, when necessary<\/li>\n<li> support for inventory reconciliation<\/li><\/ul>\n<p>As previously discussed, industry-specific test protocols largely focus on cannabinoids, terpenes, and a wide variety of contaminates, including excess water. However, as regulations continue to be in a state of flux and not particularly standardized, most LIMS developers are including the ability for users to adjust their protocols and even add new ones. And while CoC functionality is not entirely foreign to generic LIMS, it's particularly important in an industry where currently transporting even a cannabis test sample across state lines can create huge problems.\n<\/p><p>In cases where daily sample processing is infrequent and only a couple of chromatography machines are used, laboratories may weigh a decision between a LIMS and a chromatography-specific CDS, although the ability to produce an acceptable certificate of authenticity (CoA) and document the CoC are still factors, along with any state reporting requirements.\n<\/p><p><b>Cannabis LIMS solutions<\/b>\n<\/p><p>The following LIMS solutions are known to specifically offer features that support the cannabis testing laboratory:\n<\/p>\n<ul><li> <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Bika_LIMS\" title=\"Bika LIMS\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"0428bec40f5e78521f09ec45b90d1f0c\">Bika LIMS<\/a><\/li>\n<li> <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=CannaQA_LIMS\" title=\"CannaQA LIMS\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"5379532d8de7a77ac0f896a9440acad7\">CannaQA LIMS<\/a><\/li>\n<li> <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=CGM_LABDAQ\" title=\"CGM LABDAQ\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"a6bd926f89a503530f00054d1b77db1e\">CGM LABDAQ<\/a><\/li>\n<li> <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=CloudLIMS\" title=\"CloudLIMS\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"292ce03ef87cdce56e9615cf3b344e37\">CloudLIMS<\/a><\/li>\n<li> <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Confident_Cannabis_LIMS\" title=\"Confident Cannabis LIMS\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"6760c3b8b3d12323201187196190d15c\">Confident Cannabis LIMS<\/a><\/li>\n<li> <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Element_LIMS\" title=\"Element LIMS\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"466595f6ade20fa13d711b0652a0ac27\">Element LIMS<\/a><\/li>\n<li> <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=LIMS_ABC\" title=\"LIMS ABC\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"3b4a30fdf3cf3a951ee9c29c495046b3\">LIMS ABC<\/a><\/li>\n<li> <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Matrix_Gemini\" title=\"Matrix Gemini\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"5061cee66d3d0a2d0b7eb19619aa28c1\">Matrix Gemini<\/a><\/li>\n<li> <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Omega_LIMS\" title=\"Omega LIMS\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"46734499a45c1e4f5abdeb394afb55d0\">Omega LIMS<\/a><\/li>\n<li> <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=PharmWare\" title=\"PharmWare\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"356fcbc63b9e3fc630c929d1b51e0c22\">PharmWare<\/a><\/li>\n<li> <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=QBench\" title=\"QBench\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"4680ea86561bd91c9c8344c6ee947992\">QBench<\/a><\/li><\/ul>\n<h4><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"CDS\">CDS<\/span><\/h4>\n<p>Scientists on the research side of cannabis are certainly using CDSs from Agilent, Thermo Scientific, Waters, and other to manage the data coming out of their chromatography equipment<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-PurschkeDevelop16_106-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-PurschkeDevelop16-106\">&#91;106&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-AlbertiniDeterm15_107-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-AlbertiniDeterm15-107\">&#91;107&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-LaytonAnalysis17_108-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-LaytonAnalysis17-108\">&#91;108&#93;<\/a><\/sup>, and slowly but surely some of those CDSs are beginning to also support spectrometer data management in a similar way.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-DaviesCentral16_109-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-DaviesCentral16-109\">&#91;109&#93;<\/a><\/sup> Additionally, some chromatography system developers will collaborate with CDS vendors to develop software drivers\u2014code that essentially acts as a translator between a device and a program\u2014so chromatography devices can interact fully with the CDS.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-ShimadzuWaters_110-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ShimadzuWaters-110\">&#91;110&#93;<\/a><\/sup>\n<\/p><p>The CDS likely has a place in the cannabis testing lab as well, though it may depend on the lab's data management needs and goals. In more complex labs with multiple instruments and significant daily processing workflows, a LIMS may make more practical sense.\n<\/p><p><b>CDS solutions<\/b>\n<\/p><p>Some vendors like Thermo Fisher Scientific\u2014discussed in the next chapter\u2014offer a CDS in conjunction with its other chromatography systems marketed for the cannabis testing industry. Other common CDS options include:\n<\/p>\n<ul><li> <a href=\"https:\/\/www.limswiki.org\/index.php\/PerkinElmer_Inc.\" class=\"extiw\" title=\"limswiki:PerkinElmer Inc.\" rel=\"external_link\" target=\"_blank\">Chromera<\/a><\/li>\n<li> <a href=\"https:\/\/www.limswiki.org\/index.php\/Bruker_Corporation\" class=\"extiw\" title=\"limswiki:Bruker Corporation\" rel=\"external_link\" target=\"_blank\">Compass Hystar<\/a><\/li>\n<li> <a href=\"https:\/\/www.limswiki.org\/index.php\/Waters_Corporation\" class=\"extiw\" title=\"limswiki:Waters Corporation\" rel=\"external_link\" target=\"_blank\">Empower 3<\/a><\/li>\n<li> <a href=\"https:\/\/www.limswiki.org\/index.php\/Shimadzu_Corporation\" class=\"extiw\" title=\"limswiki:Shimadzu Corporation\" rel=\"external_link\" target=\"_blank\">LabSolutions<\/a><\/li>\n<li> <a href=\"https:\/\/www.limswiki.org\/index.php\/Agilent_Technologies,_Inc.\" class=\"extiw\" title=\"limswiki:Agilent Technologies, Inc.\" rel=\"external_link\" target=\"_blank\">OpenLAB CDS<\/a><\/li>\n<li> <a href=\"https:\/\/www.limswiki.org\/index.php\/H%26A_Scientific,_Inc.\" class=\"extiw\" title=\"limswiki:H&amp;A Scientific, Inc.\" rel=\"external_link\" target=\"_blank\">PC\/Chrom<\/a><\/li><\/ul>\n<h4><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Seed-to-sale\">Seed-to-sale<\/span><\/h4>\n<p>The use of <a href=\"https:\/\/www.cannaqa.wiki\/index.php?title=Seed-to-sale\" title=\"Seed-to-sale\" class=\"wiki-link\" data-key=\"bac2ef9dbf9d2112c3116b3a683f77f0\">seed-to-sale<\/a> software is an emerging trend that is only tangentially related to laboratory testing of cannabis. Rather than at testing laboratories, seed-to-sale software is found at cultivation sites, production facilities, and dispensaries, and that software is typically designed to be able to integrate with testing laboratory or other software. The goal: create a complete record of transaction, from the grown plant to the lab, producer, and seller. This sort of tracking is mandated in various ways by many U.S. states with legalization laws. \"It\u2019s there to prevent the diversion of marijuana, which the federal government still lists as a Schedule I substance, the most dangerous class of drugs,\" wrote Daniel Rothberg of the <i>Las Vegas Sun<\/i> in December 2015. \"Tracking also ensures product safety, assists with audits and helps facilitate recalls.\"<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-RothbergSoft15_111-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-RothbergSoft15-111\">&#91;111&#93;<\/a><\/sup> This type of software is able to track plant yields, attempted theft or diversion, patient preferences, extraction methods, batch weights, and various financial statistics for analysis.<sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-SmythTrack16_112-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-SmythTrack16-112\">&#91;112&#93;<\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"rdp-ebb-cite_ref-RothbergSoft15_111-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-RothbergSoft15-111\">&#91;111&#93;<\/a><\/sup>\n<\/p><p><b>Seed-to-sale software vendors<\/b>\n<\/p><p>The following vendors are a representative sample of those who offer a
